animal.description: Buffy is one gentle giant. She is a large dog, but is calm and doesn't jump on people. She loves to run and play with toys as well as other dogs and likes everyone she meets. She would be good with other dogs, kids, and cats. If you would like more information, please contact SCHS at 870-269-5200 or visit her at our shelter at 17379 Highway 9, Mountain View, Arkansas. You can also go on-line and complete an adoption application at schspets.org. UPDATE: Buffy just entered the Paws in Prison Program in Calico Rock for 8 weeks of training. She will receive obedience training, house trained, crate trained and learn tricks too. She will graduate mid February.

(Much prettier in person! He was very excited during his photoshoot so we had trouble settling him down. He has two different colored eyes... very rare!)
Glitzen was transferred from Glynn County Animal Control. He is beautiful, isn't he? We think he looks kind of looks like a little reindeer, too. Glitzen also has beautiful eyes that seem to look right through you. Different colors, which makes me think of the old saying "one eye on earth and the other on heaven". They are definitely intriguing. He also has some amazing ears! Glitzen has lots of energy, so will definitely do best with an active family with time to play and redirect all that energy in a positive direction. He does not appear to have had a lot of training at only 11 months of age. However, he is also old enough to pick it up right away. Glitzen is just a really loveable guy who is looking for a really loveable family...for life. He is neutered, microchipped, current on core vaccines and has tested negative for heartworms. Email humanesociety@hsscg.org for an application for Glitzen. You will fall in love with his amazing looks, personality and energy.

animal.description:
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS
Fenced yard
Canine sibling in her new home

Have you ever seen eyes as pretty as mine? I didn't think so. My name is Snow but it really can be changed to something else any time!!

I am a young girl..appx 1 1/2 years old and weight just 25lbs. I was taken from a situation where I was not cared for and not paid much attention to and while I am so much better than when I came to my foster home I still get scared easily. I am timid at first but I get over that pretty quickly. My foster mom says I am the biggest cuddle bug ever. Did I mention my awesome eyes? I need another dog in my new home that is close to my size because bigger playful dogs still make me feel insecure but I do love to play. I walk great on a leash and going for walks is the best. I am crate trained and getting the hang of pottying outside but I need to be kept on a schedule for that. So what do you think? Am I the god for you??

If you would like to meet Snow send us an email to theloveofk9s@yahoo.com and we will get back with you as quick as we can.

Adoption donation pays for all vetting....my spay, a heart worm test, all vaccinations, deworming, flea prevention, a microchip and a wellness exam

animal.description:
In memory of Josephine Catanese
Grandma Great's Special Transport

A transport in memory of Josephine Catanese, better known as Gram. A special mother, grandmother, great-grandmother, sister, aunt, cousin, and friend. Gram's life centered around her family. She loved us, listened to us, taught us, encouraged us, advised us, and was always there for us. Gram had many pets through the years from fish and birds to cats and dogs. Most of which were acquired by her family and brought to her home where they stayed and never looked back. All of these animals weren't just animals, they became a part of her family. She even cared for the stray cats in her neighborhood, making a cat house with heating pads, plenty of canned and dry food, water, and medicine if needed. She exemplified love and kindness every day of her life. This transport in honor of our Gram is a continuation of her love and kindness of all animals.

Please read EVERYTHING below if you are interested in this dog! We are getting so many applications for Ivy and we love this girl and she is a blast to live with, but she is not for everyone. We've received applications for her from humans that work full time and there is no other dog and another where the humans wanted a dog to alert them if someone comes to the door.....Please read as we want Ivy happy and we want you happy.

Ivy was born around October 15, 2019, and weighs about 17 pounds. Ivy came in with 6 puppies that were only days old. Ivy was an incredibly attentive mother and her pups are now grown. It's Ivy's turn to live the pampered life! Ivy is ADORABLE! She loves to cuddle in the evening when the day is done, but during the day she is playing with the other dogs, running, racing, having a ball and she is very agile! We found her balancing on the bottom rungs of the kitchen stool the other day - just for fun. Ivy is leash trained and loves her daily walks, she's so curious about everything outside! She makes us laugh every day! Ivy is good with other dogs and with kids and rides well in the car. Ivy was introduced to a cat the other day and she didn't pay any attention to it. She also loves to snuggle!
UPDATE FROM FOSTER MOM: Ivy is very affectionate - she loves people very quickly. She is very happy to cuddle up with you at night in your favorite spot. She would like someone that is home most of the time. Ivy is deaf - you can vacuum right next to her and she doesn't move. She will lay in a dog bed in whatever room you are in. She does not do well in a crate, while you are not home. She does do well in a crate in the car though. She is a climber and very clever. A home with a lot of fine antiques would not be the best fit for her. And it's not unusual for us to find her on the kitchen counter or table or jumping in your micro-green planter. We know that she enjoys quiche and if that is gone the golumpki is fair game - you will not be able to leave food unattended. And she adores helping you with your paperwork whether it's shuffling paper or knocking your laptop on the floor. She would like a spot where she can look out the window - maybe she is part cat?? A wood fenced yard would be good for her because we are pretty sure she can climb a chain link.

The Adoption Fee for this dog is $500.00
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES

We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

animal.description:
Name: Ludo
Age: 3 Years 8 Months (approx)
Breed: Mixed Breed
Adoption Fee: $275.00

Ludo is a a very happy-go-lucky boy who came to the shelter because his owner was moving and not able to take him. Ludo is a silly pup and wins the gold medal for biggest goofball! He gets sooooo excited when it's his turn for walks and playtime. His chunky butt wiggles in delight and he's always smiling! He bounds through the fields with his nose to the ground searching for whatever little creatures are lurking below! Ludo does enjoy playing with toys and also loves a good belly rub!

Ludo knows his basic commands, is housebroken, neutered and current on vaccinations. Ludo currently weighs 85 pounds and hopes his new adopter will help him continue his weight loss journey to live his best life. 

Ludo really loves the company of ladies and can be fearful of men. With patience and reassurance, he has been learning there are nice men in this world and has shown more trust when allowed the time he needs. Ludo's ideal home will be a home where he is the only pet. Children should be 14+ and he will do best in a low foot traffic area. He's hunk of chunk you will fall in love with! 

We kindly ask, IF YOU HAVE QUESTIONS regarding Ludo PLEASE EMAIL:

 adoption@popememorialcvhs.org


*********************************************

How To Adopt a Pet

We are currently offering adoptions by appointment only, due to the Coronavirus. The Adoption Center remains closed to drop-in visitors.

The process to schedule an appointment begins with the submission of an application, which can be found on our website. Once the application is approved, we will reach out to you to schedule an appointment. Please bear with us, the new process has slowed our response time.

If you do not see an animal that would fit into your home, we highly recommend checking our website weekly as new animals may become available. We do not offer a waitlist for specific breeds, types, etc. 

As always, adoptions are first come, first serve, meaning the applicant who is approved first gets their choice of available appointment times and thus his/her choice of animals to meet and adopt. We are not able to extend holds on any animals at this time, so we ask interested adopters to make their adoption decision during their appointment and be prepared to take their new pet home with you.

The easiest way to communicate with us with any questions is via email to: 

adoption@popememorialcvhs.org


No phone calls please - Submit an application here ----> 

https://popememorialcvhs.org/adoption-application

Reggie is a friendly male Hound/Terrier or perhaps even Shar Pei mix??? We honestly do not know and are only guessing! He is approx 2 years old and around 40 lbs.

Reggie is friendly with other dogs, good with kids, but not a fan of cats. He's playful and also

a bit of a ham! If allowed, he'll gently jump up to put his paws on your waist so you can more easily cradle him. He's always curious to know what's going on in the kitchen. Though constantly hoping for a snack, he is polite around food. He stands back while his food is served and only dives in after server has stepped aside. He learned to sit within the first week in foster home.

Reggie

likes to play with other dogs. He's still working on leash training, and learning not to pull or weave side to side. Reggie always interested in other people and pets walking and does barks when he sees them. He has lots of puppy energy, can jump straight up off the ground and likes to chew things he finds laying around. Reggie doesn't jump up on furniture, though if invited to sit on your lap he would! Reggie is a sweet boy and is looking for a family to give some snuggles to!

animal.description:
Meet Nyla! Nyla is an approximately 2-year-old, spayed female, weighing 35-40 lbs. 

NyNy came into the RAD Rescue family on September 26, 2020 after being trapped. 

Since being in foster we have learned a lot about Nyla. She is housebroken, crate trained, walks well on a leash, and seems to prefer smaller dogs although she has warmed up to larger dogs when given time. 

NyNy has been around goats and stayed away. She showed slight curiosity for the tortoises but decided they weren’t worth her time. She met a cat a couple of times, both times she wanted to get away from the cat as quickly as possible. 

Nyla is shy when meeting new people but once she warms up to you she is very loving and will even play with you. She bounces around when happy and playful with her ears bouncing too earning her the nickname Jellybean. 

Jellybean doesn’t appreciate being left home alone but she tolerates it, maybe tearing up her blanket to show you her displeasure. She would much prefer someone who she could hang out with during the day. 

All in all, Nyla is a really sweet pup who would love a doggy friend to play with in her forever home but she may do just fine without one. She would likely do best with no young kids as certain sudden movements (like grabbing her collar) can freak her out. 

If you are interested in adopting Nyla please submit an application with RAD Rescue Inc.

animal.description:
Diamond is an Irish Terrier mix, she is around 6 years old. She is approximately 45 lbs.

Diamond is a sassy little doe-eyed girl, weighing about 35 lbs. She is a terrier mix and has medium length hair.

Diamond will need a person in her life who can understand her. She is very sweet and enjoys cuddling and curling up on the couch with you for movie night. She knows a few cues (sit, wait, kennel, comes when called) and is generally very well behaved. She does not chew on inappropriate items. Diamond is perfectly potty trained and is also crate trained. She walks pretty well on a leash, too.

However, Diamond lacks confidence and therefore can be very shy when meeting new people. She can be defensive of her body when she is unsure, so she does need time to learn to trust her humans before they try to interact with her physically too much. She is food motivated, so that is one good way to help build a bond with her. She just needs her new person to take things very slowly with her so that she can learn to trust them on her own schedule. Once she trusts you, she will be your cuddle buddy forever.

For that reason, Diamond would do best in a home that doesn't have a lot of traffic, visitors (or she should have a safe place to hang out while visitors are over) or young children. She tends to get nervous when there is a lot of comotion or if she is uncertain about things.

Diamond does like other dogs, but she can be a bit resource-guardy with her food, toys, and even her person. She would thrive in a place where she has boundaries about what space is hers and what is not, and where she can eat her meals away from other dogs. She would need to live with dogs who can respect her cues about her space. Her person will need to help guide Diamond as to appropriate responses to other dogs sharing her space.

Diamond enjoys going in the car. She may get a little anxious, but she is getting better about this.

Overall this pretty gem just needs someone who can meet her halfway with her wants and needs, love her but still lovingly guide her when she needs it. Her adorable single floppy ear and her deep, soulful eyes will capture your heart in no time.

Also, I made her an FB album that anyone can view. That is here: https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.10225067257659353&type=3

Diamond is on anti anxiety medication that would run around $20/month.

If you are interested in meeting Diamond, please complete an online application at https://hopeanimalrescueofiowa.duplie.com/forms/196/dog-application

Adoption fee is $250 which includes spay/neuter, microchip, and age appropriate vaccines.

animal.description:
Hello Everyone! My name is Hank.  I am a 1 1/2 year old Bully Mix male who loves to play.  One of my favorite things to do is to chase the squirrels in my backyard.  I love chewing on bones, bully sticks and all of my chew toys.  I love running, and boy can I jump! My humans and I love to play catch and tug-of-war with some of my favorite rope toys.  Walks with my humans are my absolute FAVORITE thing to do.  Speaking of my humans, unfortunately, I need to find a new home because the small humans have recently been diagnosed with pretty severe allergies to dogs. They have tried everything to be able to keep me but it just has been enough.  But that's ok, because I have A LOT of love to give my next family.  I I love laying on my humans' laps and getting lots of ear scratches and belly rubs.  I don't get along with other big dogs, they scare me.  However, I do get along with little dogs really well, but I can play a little rough with them sometimes.  I am crate trained (I love my bed in my crate as well.) I love having lots of space to run and chase squirrels and birds.  My humans have done a great job of keeping up on my vet care.  I am neutered, micro-chipped and up-to-date on all of my vaccines.  I have even had regular heartworm tests (yes, they are negative.)  I hope I can find a good fun loving home and I can't wait to meet you.

Due to the current events, the rescue is not able to host adoption events.  Please fill out an application and we will conduct phone interviews and set up outdoor meet and greets! www.thegooddogrescue.org

animal.description:
BLIND

NEEDS SUBMISSIVE COMPANION DOG

Rye is a wonderful, gentle, and cuddly girl. She is blind but adapts really well to her environment. She is able to get around her foster family's house, find her food and water bowl, and play with toys. She has learned sit and plays with her dog sibling in her foster home.

Rye's ideal family must have a companion dog and minimal stairs for her safety. A fenced backyard would be a plus but not necessary. She likes to be outside sniffing around and going on walks.

She is potty trained and does fine confined to an area or in a crate. Rye would love to cuddle in your bed. She's about 55 pounds. She hasn't been around cats or kids but we are pretty sure she would do just fine. She is very sweet and loving.

If you are interested, complete the
Adoption Application
on our website at
www.NeedyPaws.org
and we will contact you.

Adopters must live within an hour's drive of St. Louis, MO.

Rye's adoption fee is $250.00, which includes up-to-date vaccinations, heartworm testing and preventative, spay/neuter and microchip.

We are a 100% foster-based rescue and all of our dogs live in approved foster homes. We are dedicated to finding the best Forever Homes, and will perform home visits and conduct veterinarian and reference checks for each potential adopter.

animal.description:
This lovely girlie is Alley! She was found as a stray, scavenging for food and shelter among a number of farms. Alley came to us covered in fleas and dirt, and severely underweight. One of her most important jobs in her foster home these days is to put on much needed weight. Even though life has not been kind to Alley, she did not hold a grudge against anyone, and is in fact, more than ready to share her love and affection with anyone who is willing to share a moment with her! She will absolutely melt in your arms if you want to spend some time giving her head scratches and gentle pets. Alley has such a wonderful temperament - she is always happy and ready to greet you with a big pyr hug :) Despite having limited exposure to living with people, Alley has wonderful house manners. Nonetheless, she is hoping that her furever family will help her with some more training so that she can become the pyrfect girl for them. This girl is hoping to have her very own furever family to cuddle with in time for the holidays. Will you open your heart and show Alley all the wonderful things there are in this world?

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Senior Hearts Rescue and Renewal is the only licensed senior dog rescue organization in Western Pennsylvania. We do not have a shelter or a public facility. ALL of our dogs reside in foster homes in the greater Pittsburgh, PA area. 

We are a 100% volunteer organization. Please respect our volunteers' time. If a dog is listed on PetFinder, he/she IS available for adoption. We cannot reply to messages, phone calls, and emails about a dog until we have received, reviewed, and approved an adoption application. 

Our ADOPTION application is found at www.seniorhearts.org Completing this application is the first step in our adoption screening process. You MUST complete the application in its entirety in order to be considered as a potential adopter.  Please select "More About Us" for further details on our adoption requirements.  You can meet a dog ONLY after we have completed our adoption approval process.

If you are looking at the dog below, it most certainly means the dog is available for adoption. We will not respond to questions asking if the the dog is available. 

We look forward to receiving your application in hopes that you are able to meet our adoption requirements and provide this dog with a loving furever home.

And now a little about super cute Bandit.
I’m 10 years young and weigh 13lbs. I’m a most handsome little guy, aren’t I?

I’m a shy guy, but once I get to know you, I might stick to you like Velcro. I’m a good snuggler too. 

I enjoy long walks and playing with a dog sibling. I do require a dog sibling in my furever home. I’m sure we can cause some good trouble together. After all of that, I like to get some good couch time in watching Netflix.

I am a doxie. So if you don’t like barking, then I’m not the dog for you. Oh no kids in my furever home please. And no cats either, after all I am a doxie!

I’m a sweet, happy, sassy, snuggly guy with a ton of love to give. I can be adopted within a two-hour radius of Pittsburgh, PA. If you are interested in giving me a furever home, you must first complete the adoption application at www.seniorhearts.org

animal.description:
Morgan, 1 yr., neutered, Kelpie/Anatolian mixMORGAN! Approximately 1 and a few months year old. Looks like a chocolate and fawn Kelpie and Anatolian shepherd. His DNA test would be interesting to see!
The shelter had him listed as a "she", and there was a gender reveal once he allowed his tummy to touched!
This handsome guy and his sister, Marlo, have had quite the journey to get here. They were confiscated from a property with too many dogs, and had apparently just existed, zero socialization or handling. They were confiscated with some other dogs.
The leash was definitely a foreign experience for both. Shelters don't like this, so last call for these two, made it out on their final hour thanks to a village of people to provide transportation, vetting and boarding, eventually getting them here.
I've been working hard with Morgan since July 2020! He walks beautifully on leash and comes to his name. I could probably let him off leash completely, but mostly I let a long line drag. He's not a heeler or a border collie. He's got more of the guardian working mentality, and he's independent!
I can see his wheels turning when I call him to come to me. Weighing out the ROI, a little more freedom and a treat? Or me in a huff when I reel him in. He's figuring it out! Makes much more sense to stay with me and come when called.
Morgan is an awesome dog. He's about 75 lbs, and just filling out into the dog he will be. He really is magnificent.
He's sweet and curious! He loves, I mean loves, my 90 lb male dog Romeo, he just loves the confidence in this older pack leader I think. He's very respectful of my older gals. Gentle and cautious with fragile 16 yr old Bonnie, and Tory is his home girl, gangster, even at 14, and she loves to play with Morgan. Morgan gets along with all the dogs, but has taken special liking to some, like cute little Willie.
I've come to really love this boy and I'm so proud of his progress! As hard as this is, the goal always was to get Morgan a home of his own. It's time for him to transfer his allegiance to another pack.
So definitely another dog or 2 in his future. He seems to have some prey drive on the trail. But that doesn't preclude him from being introduced to a cat. He really is a very gentle giant.
Morgan came here with exposure to nothing. So everything was new for him. His world is opening up for him a little at a time and he's up for it! I take him on neighborhood walks now as well as nature hikes. And he does great with his harness or on a collar.
So the needs and wants for Morgan are other dog/s, a large yard, and owners who are active and up for training a young, intelligent dog. And expanding his horizons.
Photos updated at:https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?vanity=cchdrescue.org&set=a.2625544704328259
Adoption fee is $400 and includes sterilization surgery, vaccinations, flea & tick abatement, worming, transportation to us, microchipping + chip registration. Also covers care for all the dogs while in rescue.
To download an application to meet Morgan: http://cchdrescue.org/adoptionprocess.html or email: info@cchdrescue.org
Central Coast Herding Dog Rescue, is a Rescue Alliance partner, a federally recognized 501(c)3 non profit organization, dedicated to finding great dogs, great homes. County of San Luis Obispo Animal Service Operating Permit #C2649. Thank you for reading about Morgan, and thanks for considering rescue!

animal.description:
***In Need of a Foster Home or Adopter!!***

Hi, I'm Cole! I'm a very handsome 4 year old, 65 pound Lab mix. I'm a playful and sweet guy who's looking for a special home. I'm a charming fella with good looks to match (if I do say so myself!) All the ladies love me and I like them in return. I get along with all dogs but if my forever home has another dog, it should ideally be lady or a very mellow fella. Whatever dog it is, they need to understand the concept of personal space. I'd also be perfectly happy to be an only dog. I will need a special home that understands I need to be able to do my own thing. I love people, but again, I am more of an introverted kind of guy. I'd really love a quiet home with an easy mellow atmosphere and just a few special people to adore. I am not suited to a a first time dog owner. I need someone with dog experience- no exceptions. I am not suited to a home with children under the age of 16. My ideal home would be a place where someone is around in the day as I really enjoy being with my people. I am incredibly good in the house. I am house trained, have great house manners, neutered, am up-to-date on vaccines and preventatives and I'm ready to find my forever home!

The adoption fee for this dog is $350 which includes routine vetting and spay/neuter.

***Please note that our first step is submitting an application (it does not commit you in any way but allows us to discuss with you if you and the dog are a good fit). In addition, an important step in approving adoption applicants is to complete a vet check. Vetting of current and past pets is very important to us, thus we will be speaking with the vet(s) listed on your application to ensure that your current and previous pet(s) are kept up to date on vaccines (including rabies), spayed or neutered, maintained on appropriate monthly preventatives and examined annually by your vet.***

To complete an online application, please click here and email Crystal at cwoodlovepaws@gmail.com

**If you're viewing this on Petfinder, please visit www.lovepawspg.org to complete our non-binding application.**

animal.description:
Hi!  I’m Odyfuss, a 3-year-old Heeler mix.  I am a handsome, playful and super affectionate boy who is ready for a fresh start.  I love treats, will quickly sit for one & take it from you gently. I also love playing with squeaky toys,  exploring my surroundings and being around people. I don’t jump up on people but I will jump on the couch to get snuggles from you. 

I am pretty much potty trained so just keep me on a good schedule so I can do my business outside. I do pull on a leash when I am first on it but I settle down quickly after the initial excellent wears off.  A training collar will help, as will a backyard to run in or a doggie park to play in.  

I’d be happy to share my new home with other dogs, cats or kids so what are you waiting for?  Contact the shelter and set up a time to come visit me. You can teach them 972-382-3647 ext 4 or adoptionsmoh@gmail.com. 

Once vetted I’ll be ready for my forever home.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Glacier Gray is intelligent, eager to please, loyal, a fast learner. He's beautiful, soft and super cuddly. He's potty trained and crate trained. He knows sit, shake and down. Gray is super athletic. He loves to go on walks and runs. He's not food or toy aggressive after he's established that he's the Alpha, but should be an only dog. He really wants to be number one and the only one. He gets jealous when affection and attention is shown to the other dogs. He loves playing with stuffed animals, chewing on bones and being rewarded with treats and affection. He responds only to love, safety, consistency and calm.

Gray loves being outside and inside. Gray has anxiety about riding in the car. He needs to be crated in a car. Finally, Gray's biggest issue is his reactivity or trigger to stress and his short temper. Gray would do best with a single human household.

Zuri is a very nice dog that gets along well with other dogs. She is crate and house trained, and very well behaved. She does well with adults and with kids and will make a great addition to any home.

animal.description:
Meet Yukon! He is a fun and goofy 2 year old Husky who weighs about 50 lbs. It has been a long road for this guy. Before he joined the rescue, he was hit by an 18 wheeler, which landed him in the shelter with a broken leg and pelvis. The shelter vet did surgery on his leg and had a pin and plate put in, but the broken pelvis did not need surgery, just crate rest for 6 weeks. It is a miracle he even survived! When we took Yukon back for his post surgery check-up, we learned that the plate and pin in his leg were actually too big and had caused a major infection. Poor Yukon had to have surgery on his leg again. Dr. Dean at Mustang Surgical had to remove the plate and pins and replace them with an external fixture and a bone graft in order to fix the fracture and treat the infection. He is finally done with 8 additional weeks of crate rest and months of laser and water therapy and is ready for his forever home! This is what Yukons foster Mom has to say about this boy: Yukon loves car rides, ice cubes, toys and treats. He is learning basic commands and is crate trained and potty trained. He is such a sweet boy who loves to be with his people! His ideal home would be an active home with another dog that likes to play." Due to his breed, no apartments please. We are dedicated to rescuing dogs in shelters, dogs in abusive or neglectful situations, and dogs surrendered by their owners because of difficult circumstances. We place dogs in loving, responsible, committed permanent homes, following a comprehensive adoption process, which includes taking considerable care in finding good matches and educating prospective adopters about the responsibilities and costs of bringing a dog into their homes and lives. Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, microchipped, receive all appropriate veterinary care and treatment, and placed in nurturing foster homes while they await placement in their permanent homes. We assist dogs in distress without regard to age, breed or ease of placement. Dogs in the greatest need take priority. Finally, we strive to work with shelters and other rescue and humane organizations to develop a network of supporters and volunteers in order to create a better world for homeless dogs.

animal.description:
Xena has not had an easy life. She was originally found on Dowdy Ferry Road in Dallas, which is a huge dumping ground for dogs. She was then taken to Dallas Animal Services to do her stray hold, but no one came looking for her. 
When she joined the rescue, she had a severe Upper Respiratory Infection that cleared up with the help of medication. A few weeks later she was rushed to the vet after collapsing, revealing that she had Vasculitis, a condition that attacks the blood vessels and limits blood circulation to certain parts of the body. In Xena's case, she became unable to walk and her back legs would collapse underneath her. With the assistance of antibiotics, Xena was able to walk again! 
Unfortunately, her problems weren't over yet. She then suffered from bloat where her stomach blew up to the size of a cantaloupe. Thankfully, after a successful surgery Xena pulled through once again! 
Her last challenge to overcome was Megaesophagus, a condition where the esophagus is enlarged making it impossible to keep food or water down. This condition arose suddenly and disappeared just as fast. Xena ate in an adorable doggy high-chair for a couple of months and had limited water intake along with medication until when suddenly, one day she could keep her food and water down without throwing up! 
Xena has proven so many times that what doesn't kill you makes you stronger and managed to keep an adorable pittie smile on her face the entire time! She is such a joy and is so loved by everyone who meets her. She is a true warrior princess and now it is time for Xena to find her forever family. Xena is 8 years old and weighs 90 lbs. She would do best in a home with a larger sized dog who likes to play or she would be fine be an only dog and getting all of the love herself. She loves toys! Even though she has been to training, she still gets overly excited on walks when she sees other dogs. No cats or apartments please. Also due to her size, children over the age of 10 years old would be best. She loves little kids, but does not know her size and may knock them down on accident.

animal.description:
*INQUIRIES SENT THROUGH PETFINDER WILL NOT BE ANSWERED AS WE DO NOT HAVE THE MANPOWER TO RESPOND TO THEM. PLEASE COMPLETE OUR ADOPTION APPLICATION INSTEAD*

Malachi-TX is with his family in Pasadena, TX. Please read ALL the information in his listing before applying for him. If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for him, please complete our adoption application at http://www.idogrescue.com/adoption_application. If you have completed an application in the last 3 months and meet the requirements for Malachi’s new home, you can email us at rescue@idogrescue.com and let us know you are interested in him.

We will review your application and let you know if you made our short list of applicants. We base our adoption decisions on what is in the best interest of our dogs. Please note our adoption policies are in place for the safety and welfare of our dogs - your understanding is appreciated. We are all volunteers and have jobs, families, pets of our own to care for - we do the best that we can to get back to you in a timely manner. We believe in taking time to go through our thorough process to try to match the dog with the best fit for that dog. Our adoption process may take 2-4 weeks. You must be approved to adopt before we will schedule a meet and greet. We expect approved adopters to visit the dog in his foster home within a short period of time of being approved to adopt the dog. Our adoption process involves vet and personal reference checks, phone interviews and a home visit.

MEET MARVELOUS MALACHI-TX!

*AGE: 5 years (born July 2015)
 
*WEIGHT: 29 lbs
 
*FENCE REQUIREMENT: A physical fence is preferred. No electronic fence or e-collar will be allowed as we feel this would not set him up for success.
 
*COAT TYPE: wavy, low-shedding. His new family should be prepared to brush his coat regularly and for the expense of having him groomed every 6-8 weeks or so. This is approximately $100 per groom.

*ENERGY LEVEL: low to moderate. Loves to play occasional fetch with his stuffed bunny, but when he’s finished he’s done. 
 
*DOGS: He’s done great once he’s got to know them. He would be fine as an only dog. If there is a dog in his new home, he would prefer older dogs instead of a puppy. 
 
*CATS: N/A, but I think he’d do great once he got use to them.
 
*KIDS: Kids 13+. He gets stressed around small children and growls at them to let them know this. 

*CAR: Is not a fan of the car; he whines but doesn’t get car sick. He is OK with short trips of 30 minutes or so.
 
*CRATE: He is crate trained, but has not used his crate in years.
 
*HOUSE TRAINED: Yes
 
*LEASH: Yes, walks great on a leash. He enjoys walking!
 
Malachi is a 5 year old male Parti-colored mini-Labradoodle who is looking for a new home. He is with his family in Pasadena, TX near Houston. His family loves him very much but feel their home is stressing Malachi too much and want him to have a new home with a calmer environment. They have two young children and this stresses Malachi too much. Here is what they have to say about Malachi.

Malachi is a wonderful dog who was our first child and we love him so very much. He’s loyal and he loves his humans. He loves to cuddle, loves his family, is well-behaved, and loves to be petted.

Though this transition will be hard we really believe this is what is best for Malachi, not us. We got Malachi early into our marriage and he was our only child for many years. We welcomed our miracle baby two years ago and we have desperately tried to grow the bond between him and baby. As our baby has grown they have never developed a relationship that we had such high hopes for. We accepted that and have even kept them separated as best as possible. 

Malachi wants to be with his people and we didn’t find this to be fair either. Baby and Malachi are always supervised together. Malachi has never bit our children but he growls when our toddler gets too close or runs in his direction. He gets extremely anxious and will hide behind one of us or is pacing the room for a safe place to go, even with the availability of kid free space. As we know kids are not perfect we have never allowed our babies to climb on or hurt Malachi.

We have praised both dog and babies when they have a good interaction and corrected when things don’t. Usually things deescalate quickly but there has been one time Malachi snarled at me. Again, he has never bit or snapped at any one. This was completely out of character for Malachi and only happened one time. While we have tried all avenues to keep Malachi with us we feel the best interest for him is to not live with tiny humans that are loud and fast moving.

Malachi has allergies – food and environmental that have become worse since the children were born due to his anxiety around them. He chews his skin more when he is anxious. His anxiousness is heightened around the kids and this suppresses his immune system and the anxiety makes him chew more. We’ve seen multiple vets to get opinions on his allergies. We have eliminated certain food allergies and he is on a prescription rabbit food that costs $100/bag for a 6 week supply. Though he does do well on the food alone he does suffer from environmental allergies and will get occasional flare-ups. He is bathed in a special shampoo and never allowed perfume when he is groomed. When he gets allergy flares, he may get a skin infection and crusty skin. He takes antibiotics, Prednisone and Apoquel when his allergies flare.

Malachi is well-behaved. He rings bells that we have on our back door to let us know when he needs to go outside. If those aren’t there he will just sit patiently by the door until you let him out. He goes outside just to do his business so we usually wait at the door or go outside with him. If you close the door he will lightly scratch the door and when that doesn’t work he will bark to let me know he’s ready to come in.

He is allowed on our furniture and sleeps in our bed with us. He will usually sleep at the end of our bed or between our legs. Though, we have woken up to him a time or two smack dab in the middle of us sharing our pillow sleeping on his back like a human, ha!

Malachi has never showed food aggression and loves to get treats! He listens well and knows sit, stay, and come. He walks very well on leash. We have only ever had great reports when he gets groomed they say he does wonderfully and he is so sweet. He makes a wonderful companion and such a well behaved, perfect family member.

The type of home in which we feel Malachi will succeed:
-children 13+
-owner(s) willing to help him with his allergies. This may be life-long issue and may involve several vet visits over the course of his lifetime.
-calm lower-stress home

Malachi is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, crate trained and house trained. He is heartworm negative and is current on heartworm, flea/tick preventives.

ADOPTION FEE $100

OUR ADOPTION FEES RANGE FROM $100 - $750 depending on the dog. The following is a general guide, but each dog is assessed individually. It currently costs IDOG an average of over $400 for basic vet, grooming, and foster care on each dog; that does not allow for the ones who get sick, need surgery, have special needs, or are heartworm positive.

ADOPTION FEES:
Under 6 months $550 and up
6 months to 2 years $450 and up
2 years - 4 years $350 and up
4 years + $100 and up
Special Needs fee/donation assessed on individual basis

TO APPLY FOR THIS DOG, PLEASE COMPLETE THE APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE:
http://www.idogrescue.com/adoption_application

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THE FIRST STEP IS TO FILL OUT AN ADOPTION APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE AT:

IF A PET IS LISTED THEN THEY ARE AVAILABLE - WE KEEP OUR LISTINGS UP TO DATE AND REMOVE AS SOON AS ADOPTED.

NAME:  Odie
BREED:  Manchester Terrier mix
SEX:  male
COLOR:  black/tan/white
AGE:  2 yrs as of Sept 2020
WEIGHT:  15 lbs


FOSTERED BY:
LOCATED IN:


NOTES FROM FOSTER FAMILY:

Meet ODIE!    He is a real treasure, better than any 5 golden rings!   Odie was hit by a car the beginning of September and his back was broken.   He had a CT Scan and the doctors decided against surgery because they felt the risk was potentially greater than the reward.   Odie did very well on cage rest for several months followed by physical therapy and was very determined that he was going to walk again.   He was finally cleared to be neutered and is now ready to start his new life.

Overall he doesn't have a lot of restrictions but will need a single story home (no stairs) and should be limited with jumping on and off of things.

Due to COVID-19 we are a little more limited on volunteers and the availability (and safety) of home visits.   Local applications are given first priority and some out of town areas will not be able to be processed.

At this time, we will only be able to process applications that have an excellent current vet history.  If you haven’t had a pet or verifiable vet history we will not be able to process your application.   

If you are interested in adopting please complete our Adoption Application by copying and pasting the following link into your web browser: http://www.caninecastaways.org/adoption-application

For a full list of dogs we currently have for adoption use this link:  https://www.caninecastaways.org/adoptable-dogs


MEDICAL INFO:


The following has been or will be done for this dog...
- Basic Exam by Veterinarian
- Spayed or Neutered
- Heartworm Tested
- Placed on heartworm preventive
- Basic Bloodwork
- Urinalysis
- Microchipped
- Intestinal Parasite Exam and medication
- Vaccinations
- Placed on Flea preventive


ADOPTION DONATION: $250


This adoption donation helps to cover the vet expenses for this dog including heartworm preventive which is dispensed at the initial vet visit and then goes with the dog at adoption. All vet records will be provided to adopter. 

Visit us at www.caninecastaways.org

She settled in quickly to her foster home where she is housetrained and enjoys pack walks with her family. She is fostered with several dogs big and small and gets along with all of them. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Yule, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

Bella has a bit of a story and has been a repeat visitor at Kern County Animal Services. 9 visits to be exact and those were just the visits at the county shelter. Rumor has it she's also visited our city shelter. You might be wondering why she's gotten out so much. Well her family has an a disabled child who we guess was accidentally letting Bella out. Bella is very lucky that she was never hit by a car on her adventures. Life on the streets is no life for any dog. We are so thankful we can give Bella the chance at a safer life. 

Bella can be a runner, as her previous history has shown, so a home that can keep her safely contained will be a must. She also doesn't do well with cats and is reactive to dogs so a home as an only pet would be ideal for her. Her reactivity to other dogs includes leash reactivity if she sees other animals when out on walks. Other than her issues with other animals she is sweet, gentle and calm and would make an ideal companion for someone looking for their one and only furry friend. animal.description:
Shepherds are amazing and loyal companions and Champion (Champ) is no exception. He sat at the shelter with a broken scapula and although in excruciating pain it never altered his amazingly sweet personality. Champ had been picked up as a stray by Kern County Animal Services. They have no idea how he was injured but we suspect he'd been hit by a car. We scheduled an appointment with a specialist but Champ was lucky and the specialist did not recommend surgery but instead continued crate rest and slow walks to aide in his recovery. 

Champ is now fully healed and ready for adoption. He will always walk with a bit of a hitch to his step but it doesn't hinder his mobility or negatively impact his quality of life. Champ is a super sweet dog and great with people of all ages. He is not good with other animals and very reactive when he sees them. He'll need to be the only animal in his future adoptive home. 

If you've been looking for a big, beautiful, protective shepherd Champion is your boy! Apply today If you are interested in adopting a Marley's Mutts please fill out an application at http://marleysmutts.org/adoptionprocess/

PAW Animal Shelter is a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4. If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. animal.description:
Please read the dog's entire bio before you apply.  Sadly, we are no longer able to respond to every application, but will contact the one that is a good match within 3 days.
Ravioli is a little 6 yr old 5.5 lb apple headed chihuahua with beautiful big eyes, big ears and a sweet personality.  She is very sweet and pretty confident and social for such a little girl as long as she is around people knows.   As most tinies, the world of strangers can be scary for her.   She likes attention and loves snuggles with her person, she is the ultimate lap dog and will follow you around all day.  She is doing well with dogs and cats in her foster home but is bossy.    Ravioli came to us with really bad dental disease and had a cleaning and extractions.  Sadly her jaw was made weak by the rotten teeth and it broke.  She is doing well in recovery, already eating like a champ so we know in no time she will be back no normal.   She is too small for childen under 13 and super rambunctious dogs.     As many tinies she has bad knees but they dont bother her.
Most of our dogs are not available to an out of the area adoption because of difficulty to follow up.  If you do not live within a 2 hr drive of Orange County, please email us before applying to see if the dog you are interested is may be a candidate for long distance adoption.    We only make consider long distance adoptions for dogs who have been in our rescue for 6 plus months with no local candidates.
If you are interested in adopting one of our rescues, please visit our main website for adoption procedures at www.pupsandpals.net and then fill out our application.  Please note that we are all volunteers so it may take up to 3 days to process your application, but you will hear back from us if your application is a good match for the pet. 
We do not have a shelter so individual appointments must be made to meet the pet you are interested in.  Our pets are fostered/boarded all over LA and Orange County.  
This pet is altered, vaccinated, microchipped, and has had a brief temperament evaluation to help us determine what type of  a home he/she would thrive in.  Please note that we put lots of time and effort to make sure our pets are ready to be someone's perfect pet before they go home.... and to make sure that we will have the best possible match for this pet we do require an : application, interview, adoption fee and in some case a home check.  
Listed for adoption: 12/30/2020
Adoption fee: $300
PLEASE DO NOT call or email to see if a pet is available.  We update our pages daily so if he/she is pictured here in the available dogs section, we are accepting applications at this time.

animal.description:
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS
Fenced yard
a canine sibling would be great but not required in the right home

My name is Bodee. I am a Great Pyrenees/Lab mix and I am in the market for a new home. I was found roaming the neighborhood all by myself and no one ever came for me. My foster mom says I am the best boy ever and she wouldn't care if I ever left but she can't keep another dog and still be able to help the others like me with no family. I am very very thin. Way underweight my vet says. We are working on that though and I have gained a few pounds since coming here. I am great with other dogs. Even littles and I love kids. Not too sure about cats though as I haven't been around them. I am crate trained and housebroken and I love car rides. I am about 3 years old and will weigh about 100 lbs once I am at a healthy weight. 

If you would like to meet Bodee, send us am email to theloveofk9s@yahoo.com and we will get back with you as quick as we can.

Adoption donation pays for all vetting...my neuter, a heart worm test, all vaccinations, deworming, flea prevention, a microchip and a wellness exam

animal.description:
COURTESY POSTING FOR Anthony Vallejo 903-707-5254, avallejo717@gmail.com.  Information as of 12/3/20.

"Stella, 38lbs, Super cuddly, She knows sit, wait, shake and high five.  She sits and waits when you feed her, and will wait for your command to eat.  She is house trained, and walks great on a leash.  She is VERY smart, and learns and listens quickly.  She is not aggressive towards children, but does seem afraid of them when they jump and scream.  Back story:  We found and adopted her 3 years ago from the streets.  She was extremely malnourished, and decided to keep her.  Other than being skinny, she was healthy and took to our home immediately.  She lived with us and our two other older dogs (female chihuahua and male terrior mix) peacefully for 2 years.  This past year, she has expressed aggression towards our older male dog.  The aggression seems to stem around their possessiveness of my fiance.  They guard her from each other for her attention.  My old boy is almost 9 now, and I need to protect his well being, so I need to find Stella a new home.  I feel with a family where she is the only pet would be best.  She's extremely athletic, loves to play, hike, and climb."

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi I'm Minnie! I have now been in rescue for over a month and doing great. I am enjoying the company of the other dogs as well as humans of all sizes. I do have a high prey drive so should go to a home without any cats or small animals. I do like sitting on the couch and staring intently outside watching the birds and squirrels. I am learning to not jump on windows, but it's a work in progress. I love treats and will take them nicely. I no longer sleep in my kennel, I prefer a to sleep on a dog bed next to your bed. I haven't had any accidents. I love to chew on bones or laying next to you in bed or on the couch.

I am getting better with the younger two high energy dogs in my foster home, but would prefer calmer dogs. I don't think I would like a dog park - especially since I do have a high prey drive with squirrels and birds.

I had a bath and did great with it. My foster also trimmed my nails - I didn't care to have that done but was a good girl for it.

Adoption fee includes: Full veterinary exam, dental, alter, prepaid microchip, dewormed, Rabies vaccine, DAPP vaccine, Bordetella vaccine, 4DX

, flea/tick and heartworm preventative while in rescue. Adoption fee: $195.00

animal.description:
Sweet Giblet found her way to Coastal Pet Rescue over the Thanksgiving Holiday. She is a typical Lab puppy; always up for excitement and adventure, who seems to get along with most other dogs.
Still in training, she walks better with a harness and will need someone who can help her with her leash skills and other commands. She will also need a home with a fenced in yard where she can have lots of play time, and would probably do well with an active family.
Giblet will reward you daily with hugs and kisses and will make some lucky person a wonderful companion.



Our dogs are split between residence at our shelter, Camp Pawsawhile Retreat, and foster homes. Meet and greets are available by appointment only. Please complete an adopter profile to set up your meet and greet: http://coastalpetrescue.org/adopt/profile

Adoption Fees:
Kittens: $60, Cats (1 year plus): $50, Puppies: $250, Adult Canines (1 to 6 years): $200, Seniors (7 years plus): $100 (unless otherwise specified). Adoption fees are not a tax-deductible donation as allowed by IRS regulations. Adoption fees help to offset the cost of the pet's care incurred by Coastal Pet Rescue, which are generally 2 to 3 times the adoption fee amount.
Some special circumstances may change the fee; see pet's listing for actual adoption fee.

All Coastal Pet Rescue pets are current on shots, microchipped* and spayed/neutered prior to adoption. Adopters are responsible for any shots that may be due after adoption (particularly for kittens and puppies that must have three rounds of shots to be protected).

Microchip:
CPR has implanted a microchip as part of the adoption process and the chip is included in the adoption fee. However, some chip companies require a registration fee varying from $9.99 to $19.99. The registration fees are the responsibility of the adopter and are NOT included in the CPR adoption fee. Adopters may add this cost to their adoption fee to have CPR register the chip on their behalf.

30 Days Pet Insurance: 
As a Petfinder member, all adopters are entitled to a free 30 day insurance policy through PetFirst. Coastal Pet Rescue is not responsible for this policy. Adopters must call PetFirst’s toll-free number 855-710-7387 to activate the coverage. If adopters fail to call, the policy will not be activated.

animal.description:
Dink has quite an amount of energy! Pitties are an energetic breed on its own and we think Dink has a bit of another energetic breed mixed in too! Dink is super quiet in his crate, but once he’s out, he’s ready to go-go-go! Dink had to be quarantined for doggie cold when he arrived to foster so we are still getting to know how he is in a house on a daily basis. Dink is appropriately quite active and playful in the yard. He enjoys chasing toys, but he does not bring them back for fetch. Dink seems to like to learn skills for treats in non-distracting environments.

We believe he would love to be a hiking partner. He seems ok with trying new things like going new places, even the vet, so he could make a good adventure partner. He is friendly towards people he has met at the shelter he was at and in his foster home (only a handful of people due to Covid, however he was very friendly towards all). He jumps on people still, but is learning that keeping his paws on the ground will produce treats and attention and jumping does not. He is showing improvement with the jumping. He tends to swallow pieces of soft toys that he gets really into chewing so hard toys are preferred for this guy. (He does not consume random items or fluff on the floor though.) He has learned that when there is a piece of soft broken toy in his mouth that he is about to swallow, and his name is called, he can drop the piece and come to the human for a treat which has worked well for the times he has had soft toys and been allowed to chew them with high supervision.

Dink seems to either be quite excited/amped up when his toys are touched (anticipates the toy will be thrown or played tug with) OR he doesn't really want his toys to be touched when he's really into playing with them. All we have seen in foster is a few growls when his toys were physically touched and one time he stood over a toy and growl/barked after he had been intensely playing with it and a human reached for it. This does not permeate daily life (humans can walk closely by him with a toy he has without issue and touch other toys in the room that are not near him (a few feet away)). Dink can easily be managed by not taking toys from him without trading for a treat or calling him away from the toy for a treat. He responded very well to a few initial "trading for treats" sessions. Dink's adopter will be provided lifelong training support for free for this behavior from WTFR's trainer. Dink has never bitten a person in foster, however Dink would do best in an experienced adult only home so he can be successful with progress on this toy matter.

Dink had an introduction session with a neutral dog who was quickly overwhelmed by his play style and Dink did not give the dog space as he tried to walk away many times. We are concerned that Dink's easily highly excited personality around other dogs could agitate another dog to the point of high discomfort and correction from the dog. We don't think Dink would take a correction from a dog well as he easily becomes overly amped up and we don't want to see Dink in a situation with another dog where he may behave in an undesirable manner. This, plus Dink's possible desire to keep his toys to himself, leads to our belief that he would live most harmoniously in a home as the only pet. He has been non-reactive towards dogs and people on leash outside.

Dink has not shown any food guarding however we do not touch dogs while they are eating in foster nor do we take their food away. Dink eats in his crate in foster and when we latch the door by his food bowl while he is eating he does not seem uncomfortable. We do not know how Dink would feel if a dog were to come near him while he is eating or chewing on a snack stick.

Living in a home consistently with opportunities to play and exercise to get his energy out appropriately, plus basket muzzle conditioning and appropriate, safe socialization with friendly, savvy dogs could lead to Dink being able to make dog friends. We have not seen any aggressive behavior from Dink towards other dogs in foster (i.e. dogs crated next to him, when he walks by other crated dogs, when other dogs walk by his crate).

animal.description:
BamBam is a playful, silly, loving boy. BamBam is small, weighing in at 6 lbs. of cuteness. The vet thinks he is about 5 years of age, so he is still a youngster at heart. He will chase his squeaky toys and tosses them around in the air. He and the fosters dog play tug a war with their toys.  He enjoys being loved on and having attention given to him.

We don’t know his history, but it appears he was not an indoor dog. He was not housebroken but has learned to use a pee pad in the house.

He is surrounded with three foster brothers, one canine and two felines. He is cat curious and does like to chase the cat if the cat runs.

BamBam and Betty are very much bonded and would need to be adopted together. He takes care of Betty and gets a little anxious when he doesn't see her close by. He is very worried about her whenever you touch her or put her sweater on her, he will come to make sure she is ok. 

BamBam is up to date on his vaccinations, neutered and microchipped.

He is just an amazing little guy who deserves to find a home that will give him love and attention, something we don't believe he has had. He is ready for a real home and he is ready to start a new year with you!

His foster mom feels that since they are so small, she wouldn’t advise a home with small children. They would do well in an adult only home.

If you are interested in knowing more about BAMBAM and BETTY, please contact Mary Alice with any questions and to receive adoption applications for them. Email: alikat52@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
**Betty is bonded with BamBam and they must be adopted together. **

This sweet senior showed up in the backyard of her now foster family, after a cold, windy night. She was accompanied by a young male chihuahua, which we feel may be her son. She was scared, timid and dirty. When the family came outside to the yard, she ran and hid while her son, BamBam, barked. They were scared but when approached, they were very friendly.

They were brought into the home, bathe, fed and kept warm. All efforts were made to find their family, but no one ever came forth. They are now ready to find their new furever home and family.

Betty is a sweet, gentle spirited lady. Betty is a tiny little thing, just 3 lbs. of loveableness. The vet thinks she is about 7+ years of age. She wants your attention, loves to be in your lap, snuggling with you in bed. She is content to just chill. She likes to eat, walk around a little then back to bed. She likes her sweaters, as she is cold a lot. She would thrive on human companionship (aka couch potato).

She is surrounded with three foster brothers, one canine and two felines. She gets along with the dog and not interested in the cats.

Her foster mom feels that since she and BamBam are so small, she wouldn’t advise a home with small children. They would do well in an adult only home.

She may be shy at first but give her time to trust you and she will have you wrapped around her little paws!!! Once she trusts you, she will follow you around everywhere you go. She loves to give kisses. 

Betty is up to date on her vaccinations, spayed and microchipped.

She is just an amazing mellow little lady who deserves to be spoiled and pampered. Betty is ready for a real home and she is ready to start a new year with you!

She and BamBam are very much bonded and would need to be adopted together. She gets a little concerned when she doesn't see him close by.

If you are interested in knowing more about BETTY and BAMBAM, please contact Mary Alice with any questions and to receive adoption applications for them. Email: alikat52@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
***please read entire bio BEFORE applying or inquiring***

We will not adopt Tess outside of a 60 mile radius around Minneapolis/St Paul.

If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

***please read entire bio BEFORE applying or inquiring***

Tess is a 6.5 year old French Bulldog who was released from a breeder.   She weighs about 18 pounds.  Tess is NOT housetrained and has frequent accidents.  She does not understand puppy pads.  She often can drink a little too much water if allowed and urinate frequently.  She will need a family committed to working on house training and potentially looking at diapers if needed. 

In rescue,  Tess has been spayed,  had a dental, and had an umbilical hernia repaired in addition to bloodwork and regular vetting.  Tess's bloodwork showed her ALT slightly elevated in her liver.  She has been put on a hepatic supplement, but will need a bloodwork recheck in in March to recheck her results.  Her other liver numbers are in line, so her adoptive family needs to monitor her results and trend in bloodwork results over time.  If her ALT rises over time, further diagnostics up to an ultrasound may be needed as recommended by a vet. 

Tess requires a family who can support her and make sure her veterinary needs in the future are taken care of no matter what. 

Tess is good with other dogs, but is unknown with cats.  She is not living with small children.  Recommended with kids ages 8 and up. 

Applications are reviewed in the order received.  Vet references will be checked.  

Adoption fee is $425.00 + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact: Katie - kit_n_caboodle22@hotmail.com 

This dog will be at our adoption event at the Woodbury PetSmart on Saturday from 11-2 looking for a home!

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

Margaret was found as a stray in Carson California and brought to the shelter. This pretty girl had a microchip, but when the owner was called he stated he no longer wanted her.

She is now healthy as a horse and a super happy pup. She is around 8 years young and LITERALLY loves everyone! She gets along with all people and dogs. Unfortunately, this baby does not get along with kitties.

She is currently located in a wonderful foster home in Aliso Viejo and is ready to meet her furever home.

animal.description:
Handsome Clyde!
Clyde is a great 6 year old red Doberman neutered male. He absolutely loves people both adult and kids. He loves to be petted and paid attention to, and he will let you know when he is not done being petted! He has been sledding with the 12-14 year old grand kids and had a great time. He was happy to run and jump on their makeshift sleds as much as they were. He loves to run and play with other neighborhood dogs as well. His current routine is running back and forth along the fence line with the neighbors Shih Tzu's, until they get tired and cannot run any more.

Clyde is very energetic and loves his two 1-mile walks everyday. He does still pull some when he spies someone else out and about because he wants to visit everyone, but we are working on that. It will just take a little more time and patience.

He is smart and quickly learning how to wait at each street corner, as well as sit, shake, and down. He is very treat motivated for learning new things. Clyde is jumping into the car pretty easily, and getting better at car rides. They are not nearly as scary as he once thought. Whether you are spending time in your home office, kitchen or TV room, Clyde is happy to be there to help you as well. He prefers company to being alone and he will tell you when its time for a walk or to just go outside.

We think Clyde would be extremely happy to have a home where he has a 4 legged playmate he can run and play with, but he would do good if you are just willing to give him extra attention too. Clyde is not fond of crates and would not do well in one

This fabulous foster is a Doberman Rescue Minnesota foster dog.

Please read all adoption steps and policies carefully on our website. http://dobermanrescueminnesota.com/adoption-steps/

Qualified adopters are within the approved adoption area, and Adopter will be requested to visit this foster dog at the foster family home. Our foster families are generally located within a 250 mile radius of Minneapolis, MN.

All DRM dogs are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, health checked, microchipped, 4DX tested, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention.

animal.description: A year and a half old, Purebred rottweiler. Good with people over the age of 12 years old. No toddlers. very sweet, loves people, obediant, playful, good with other dogs. No farm animals or cats. Has a good temperament, high prey drive. Loves to cuddle and hang out with his peeps. Can jump a 5 foot pool fence. New owner need to have a solid brick wall minimum 6 foot tall. With nothing that can be used as a stepping stool like a fire pit or flower planter. Binterested? Our Adoption Process... If you are interested in adopting one of our fun loving not so rotten rotties, you will be asked to fill out a questionnaire that will allows us to get to know you better and to make sure the dog you are looking at is a good fit for your family and lifestyle. You can access our questionnaire by going to our website, www.rottenrottie.com click on the forms tab, and fill out the questionnaire and submit it online. After we review your answers, if we feel that the dog that you are interested in, is not a good fit for you and your family, we may recommend a different rottweiler companion. After we determine which Rottweiler(s) is the best for you, we will set up a time so that you can meet him or her at their house, where they will feel most comfortable and act as they normally do. An adoption contract will be signed to finalize the adoption and we do ask for a rehoming fee of $400 for most adults, $250 for most of our seniors 6 years and above for any rottweiler mix of any age (except puppies) . Our fees for puppies fluctuate depending on how much we had to invest into them or their litter, and weather they are purebred or a mix. These funds are necessary so that our organization may continue to rehome rottweilers. ALL of our dogs are sterilized, fully vaccinated and microchipped, heartworm tested negative and come with a collar and a leash. We have also addressed any injury or illness that they had when they came to us, or received in foster care. These problems will be disclosed to the adopter prior to adoption.

animal.description:
**If a dog/pup is still listed on petfinder we are still accepting applications on him/her. We will not respond to petfinder inquiries regarding any information already publicly posted.** Please take time to read the information provided and complete an application if interested.** Incomplete applications will not be considered.**

Hi! My name is Quincy! 
I am about 3 years old and I weigh around 14 pounds. I am neutered, current on vaccines,  microchipped, have had a dental cleaning and on heartworm and flea prevention.
Read my Facebook Bio Here: https://www.facebook.com/466968716999292/posts/1271791859850303/

My adoption fee is $425.

Please submit an application if you want to make me part of your family! 
Meet and greets are scheduled with approved adopters. 
Copy the link below and paste it into your browser for an application:

http://www.emailmeform.com/builder/form/wACc22HN2JDb60dtb465Z 


Our adoption process consists of an application, and reference checks. We do home visits when a reference check is not enough. You must be at least 21 years old to apply to adopt.
Please fill out all fields as accurately as possible. We will not process incomplete applications. 

Adoptions are made on a best home basis. If two excellent applications come in for the same dog, our policy is first in time, first in line. Our goal is to have the very best home for all our dogs. Our dogs are in private foster homes waiting to be adopted. Due to limited foster space, we are unable to hold an animal to be adopted out at a later time.

Please keep in mind that we do our best to make an educated guess as to the breeds of our rescued pets. In rescue we rarely see the parents of our dogs and puppies, and even when we do, they are usually mixed breeds as well. 

We rely solely on adoption fees and donations to provide care for our rescued animals, many of whom have incurred medical bills that are much higher than any possible adoption fee. The fees received act to help support the organization as a whole, allowing them to continue efforts to rescue animals from high-kill shelters in South Carolina and Georgia.

animal.description: Sometimes it takes someone who has experienced hard times and heartless treatment from the hand of a human to show all of us how to forgive and forget. 2-year-old Care Baer arrived at the Humane Society suffering from neglect and lack of even the most basic of needs: food, shelter, medical attention, and companionship. Thanks to the kindness and compassionate nurturing of the Humane Society volunteers, Care Baer wakes up every morning (in the clouds of Care-a-Lot) with clean living quarters and a full tummy. He shares smiles with everyone while he enjoys a romp in the bark park and shows off his sense of humor by giving the photographer a “canine raspberry”. He has a great desire to please his human as he performed literally dozens of instant sit poses while only, even if he wished otherwise, occasionally receiving a treat. Care Baer has a strong athletic stature and pulls hard on leash but is now working with a trainer and is enriching his easy-going, it’s-time-to-enjoy-life personality. He also wanted everyone to know that he prefers to be known as Baer as it perfectly reflects his lets-just-have-some-fun energies. Within the Care Baer tribe, he is called Wish Baer as he looks forward to sharing his life with a loving human.
animal.name: Care Baer  6285

animal.description: Walking next to Andre on the path to the bark park filled the human with an unmistakable feeling of comfortable self-assurance just as long-time friends share their unspoken companionship and loyalty. During the photo shoot, it is not unusual to have a canine move up quietly behind the photographer and give a gentle touch to his hand just to let him know that he is still there. The process was repeated by Andre, but with an unusual and surprisingly mellow scenario . No physical contact ensued, just the powerful puff of an air jet “nudge” to the back of the hand. Then as the human turned around, Andrea gave his best “What, me worry?” stoic pose.  How could you not smile at the creative contact?  Andre was given his name in honor of another gentle giant who lived an exemplary life of entertainment, interwoven with friendship to all. Andre has an easy-going, mellow nature and enjoys sharing time with everyone he meets.

animal.description:
Diamond is one darling dog! This 8-year-old pitty mix came to Lake Humane Society because she prefers to be the only 4-legged in the home. And trust us, you won't need another pet in the house with this smiley and huggable girl around! We dare you to not fall in love with that smile! Diamond is a happy-go lucky girl who is always ready for fun and adventure. She is active, outgoing, and extremely affectionate. Her positive energy is contagious and sure to bring you joy and warmth. Diamond would do best with kids over 10 and a family willing to provide her lots of exercise and love. Diamond has been spending lots of time with volunteers going on pawsititve adventures and they have nothing but great things to say! They describe her as the sweetest girl ever, easy walker, polite, happy, and a big cuddler! Diamond is crate and house trained, and knows sit and stay. What more can we say, Diamond would absolutely love a home for the holidays! 

All of our dogs and puppies are spayed/neutered prior to being placed for adoption. They also receive a physical examination from our veterinarian and are tested for heartworm. All of our dogs receive age-appropriate vaccinations (including rabies) and they are treated for fleas. All cats and dogs adopted from our facility are microchipped. 

For more information, please call (440) 951-6122, email adopt@lakehumane.org or visit our website at www.lakehumane.org. Thank you for choosing adoption!
