animal.description:
"Cash" is a chocolate lab mix who needs a new, loving home.  He is a friendly boy and has been in a home with three other dogs.  He is neutered and now current on all vaccinations and microchipped.  He has done well with housetraining but was rehomed to a relatives home and began marking.  They are not sure why he started marking, but could have been the new surroundings and claiming new territory?  Whatever the circumstance, he is smart and easily trained.  He is being rehomed because they have a new baby and they are unable to have enough time for four dogs.  The dogs require more exercise and attention than they are currently receiving.

The adoption fee for "Cash" is $200 and he would do best in an active family.  He is two years old and a perfect age for transitioning.  We do not adopt to families with children under the age of 5 and prefer to find homes within a 200 mile radius as we have a two week trial period before adoptions are final and we also have booster vaccinations that have followup boosters 30 days later.

If you are interested in adopting "Cash" email kathy@3dogrescue.com for an application that can be filled out online and returned.

animal.description:
Here's a great update on how Bailee is doing in her foster home (and those new photos - do you not LOVE the big smile on her face now?): 
"She is learning the stairs [to yard] really well. Maybe not all the spacial areas quite as fast, but she is picking up on going down and coming back up all on her own. She is highly food motivated and there is no issue with reaching into her dish or taking away a bone.  Bowels seem consistent, and no issues holding it to go outside.  Doesn't mind being touched, and settles down in front of the fire on a dog bed.  She is doing just fine with her crate, and doesn't complain much ever about anything. **Someone needs to cherish this sweet girl for the rest of her days.**"

And, dear reader, that's where you step in. Bailee is still in need of a home of her own. Is that you?  Here's a little more history on this sweet old girl:

Due to some major life changes in the family, including young children who are allergic, senior girl Bailee is in need of a new home ASAP. 

Bailee is a 10 yo spayed female who is also blind. She lost her sight several years ago due to unknown causes - the owner says she is 100% blind. She has lived with other dogs, but since her sight loss became more irritable and aggressive with a Labrador she lived with for years. We are told she is not good with small dogs and her owner feels she would be best in a home with no other animals and no small children. 

She is very friendly with new people and would do well with someone who has a little extra time for her. Because dogs orient so well through their nose/scent, sight loss is usually very manageable. 

Apply to adopt here: https://forms.spdrdogs.org/adoptions/

Transport to Western Washington can be arranged. A backup foster home would also be very helpful for February. Please Message us for a foster home application. 

Washington, Oregon, or Idaho only - no multi-state transports

Please visit our Facebook page for updates: https://www.facebook.com/SPDRRottweilerRescue

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Charlie Brown- Because look at my big block head!!!!. I'm a big 'ol American Bulldog & my foster momma says the "bull" part of that is right. She says I am totally bullheaded & I ignore her when she's talking.... did someone say something??? She also said I'm like a bull in a china shop. Excuse me but sometimes stuff gets in my way & it just falls over. I don't know what you expect me to do. I love every person I meet.... like A LOT!!! I love treats & I might have a slight tennis ball obsession...... ok ok, it might be a little more than a slight obsession..... I love car rides & I love long naps on the couch..... & tennis balls... I also love any kind of nylabone, femur bone & anything fuzzy with a squeaker that I can de- stuff. My foster momma says that I am a bit of a diva- I would do best as the only 4 legged baby in your house. My absolute favorite thing in life is to be snuggling on the couch touching my person with a stuffy in my mouth!! #SpoiledMuch. Charlie Brown's adoption fee is $175. He is up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, neutered, and microchipped.
All of our dogs are spayed or neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped and if over 6 months of age, heartworm tested and on heartworm preventative in their foster home.

We require an approved application to meet any of our dogs. We do not have a shelter location and will not arrange a meeting without an approved application.

We strive to make sure the bios provided for our dogs are complete and accurate; we do understand that mistakes happen, however, so if you absolutely cannot find the answer to your question in the dog's bio, you can contact us for more information.

We require a home visit for each dog we adopt out, so we adopt within a 2 hour radius of Dayton, OH. If you are outside of this radius, we encourage you to contact your local rescue or shelter.

Since that time she has come to fully appreciate the comforts of a warm and dry place to live along with a super soft blanket on which she can sleep comfortably.  She has especially come to love being with people. We are recommending a home with no small children ONLY because she is a larger dog (62.2 pounds) who gets excited when playing and she could knock a smaller child over.  Darcy plays with some male dogs but could be an only dog as well.  this girl is one of a kind.

If you are interested in Darcy, please fill out an application here:
https://www.parkvilleshelter.com/adoption-application

Alex's family had to re-home her over a year ago which totally devastated poor Alex. She was turned into a local shelter & scheduled to be put down. Luckily local rescuers pulled her from the shelter. Unfortunately we have had difficulty placing her. Alex is a very loyal gal but her confidence level needs worked with. Alex needs an experienced German Shepherd owner that is up for a short challenge, someone that is also patient & able to work with her in the areas needed. Alex does not do well in a kennel setting- She becomes very anxious & will pace. She also refuses to eat. She has been placed with two fosters over her 1 plus year searching for a new forever family & in both homes the first 3 days were the hardest. Alex is unsure of new people & will growl which is very intimidating, however, once she realizes she is safe she becomes a total lover. She is not the German Shepherd dog for a 1st time owner of the breed. She is not the dog for someone that doesn't have the time, knowledge or willingness to work with her. Adopter needs to be confident & consistent with her training. Alex was raised with 3 small children without incident. She will become very protective of her people if adopter is not able to provide the leadership needed. Leadership is a must. Adopter will need to be patient with Alex at first & limit introducing her to a lot of people. It is imperative she feels safe & you get her trust before introductions to others. 'By getting her trust 1st we will ensure success.' Home visit & references required.  Located Jackson County WV

~Cosmo is looking for an active family and a fenced yard to burn off some energy. He is a friendly, energetic boy who absolutely loves all people. He is currently living with a female dog and a toddler.
Cosmo enjoys walks and is a great cuddle buddy. He is house trained and crate trained. He is 3 years old and 40 lbs. Good with adults and children.

Cosmo is looking for a foster home and may be available through our foster to adopt program or for adoption.

Please email us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com to find out if Cosmo is the right one for you! (Local adoptions preferred - Philadelphia and tri-state area [South Jersey and northern Delaware] only.)

PLEASE READ BEFORE CONTACTING US!
We are NOT a shelter: All of our dogs live in private homes with foster families. Come and meet the Almost Home dogs and their fosters at our Meet & Greet events, where you can learn more about our wonderful dogs from the people who live with them, find out which dogs are on their way and when they'll arrive, and fill out an application to adopt or foster.

We cannot adopt to homes where electric-shock fencing systems or training collars are used. For more information on the dangers of electric-shock collars, please visit banshockcollars.ca/studies.php and http://www.hollysden.com/say_no_to_shock.htm (scroll down and click on the "Invisible Fencing Systems" link).

We do not have an online adoption application; to request an application, e-mail us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com. To speed e-mail processing time, be sure to note the name of the dog you are inquiring about in the Subject line. For Meet & Greet times and locations, visit our home page, where you also will find information on our adoption process and fees.

FOSTER FAMILIES ARE LIFESAVERS!! Can you open your heart and home for a few weeks to homeless shelter dog? Remember, by fostering a dog, you save TWO lives - that of your foster dog, and that of the dog who takes his place in the shelter! Come to a Meet & Greet and find out if fostering is for you - there's no reward quite like the feeling that you've saved a life ... or two!P

NAME:  Oscar

AGE:  6 yrs.

SEX:  Male

COLOR:  Red

COAT:  Smooth

UP TO DATE:  Yes

SPAYED/NEUTERED:  Yes                         

DHPP:  Yes    DATE:  7/13/2020

RABIES:  Yes    DATE:  10/4/19    TAG NUMBER:  32918

ADOPTION FEE:  $300.00 + $20.00 (microchip fee)

HOUSETRAINED:  Yes

CRATE TRAINED:  Yes

LEASH TRAINED:  Yes

FENCED YARD NEEDED:  Yes

SPECIAL NEEDS:  Had Surgery for IVDD

HOME W/ SMALL CHILDREN:  8 years and up

HOME W/ OTHER DOGS:           MALE:  Yes        FEMALE:  Yes

HOME W/ CATS:  No

MICROCHIP BRAND and #:  911PetChip  911002001582134  

MONTHLY HEARTWORM DATE:  17th of each month

FOSTER HOME:  Diane, aadrpresident@gmail.com

RESCUE #:  2017-12-15-03

BIO:  Oscar was adopted 2.5 yrs ago and returned to us in May due to the fact that he went down in the back. His previous owners were educated about dachshunds' weight and the risk of stairs but still allowed him to do stairs and get 6 pounds overweight. He is now back down to 14 pounds.

Our must-haves for this sweet boy include:

    A fenced yard
    CANNOT do stairs/steps
    No jumping or climbing
    Another dog to keep him company if you have to be out of the house
    His weight maintained at 13-14 pounds for his back's sake
    No apartments or high rise apartments or condos
    Needs a potty schedule

Don't think because he's had IVDD that he can't run because he can keep up with the best of them, which is why he has to have a fenced yard. He loves kids, people, and attention. If you are home a lot he would be just fine as an only dog. He is a major toy destroyer. He loves to go for short walks and doesn't pull on the leash. Oscar will always walk with a bit of a wobble, but it only adds to his charm. Please give him a chance at a lasting home, he so deserves one!  
============== Information for All Dogs/Adopters ==============

If you have questions about this dog, please feel free to contact the foster home at the email address listed above.  They have the most up-to-date information concerning the dog and would be happy to answer any questions about the animal. 

We welcome out of state and Canadian adoptions, but we will not ship any dog via cargo.  You will have to make arrangements to pick up the dog or for them to go by ground transport.  If you choose transporting by either volunteers through our organization or by paid transporter, there will be an additional $45 fee added for the required Health Certificate. 

We will not adopt into CT, RI, NH, ME, or MA due to strict laws regarding importation of dogs into those states.  If you have an issue with this, you need to take this up with your legislatures.

To understand the adoption process through AADR, please review the Adoption Information on our home page.  Transportation options are outlined on that page in Step 3.

If you are interested in adopting this Dachshund please review Read Before You Adopt and then you can complete an Application.

THANK YOU FOR YOUR INTEREST IN A RESCUE.

Please don't let the distance stand in your way of finding your newest best friend. We have volunteers that will help your "new friend" get up and down the East Coast. We just can't get them from one Coast to the other but some day we hope to have enough volunteers to do that as well.  For now, please look for dogs on your coast.

animal.description:
Hi! I am Cash a 3 year old, 84 lb. hound mix looking for my forever family. I am UTD, neutered, house broken, crate trained, and I am still learning how to walk like a perfect man on a leash. I am medium energy and would love a family to cuddle and snuggle with that loves a little adventure here and there. I have not been around cats or other dogs and would prefer a home with no little kids. I am a super healthy boy, however I do have some allergies (gotta love Florida!). A forever family sounds like a dream come true and I can not wait to find mine! 

I have to find my new forever home because I was no longer the right fit for my prior family (due to a recent situation) so my amazing foster mom took me in.

Adoption requirements are as such:


	No kids under 16
	No other animals unless experienced in slow introductions and willing to take their time 
	No apts 
	Dog experience (has owned a dog prior)


Please note, Cash is part of Happy Trails Animal Rescues rehoming program. He has not been tested or evaluated and the information gathered is from the current owners personal statements regarding health and temperament. The owner is subject to placement outside of our organization. We cannot guarantee availability.

animal.description:
Serena is a wonderful dog! The scars on her face, neck, and body tell us that she's had a rough life so far - but you would never know based on her sweet disposition and warm, affectionate personality. Serena is so loyal and eager to please her humans. She forms strong bonds with people quickly and easily. She loves to snuggle. Serena got along very well with our 2 dogs (males, 40 and 80 lbs) and was still in the process of learning how to play and rough-house with the boys on her last day with us. She is completely house-trained, crate-trained, and she walks beautifully on a leash. It has been such a joy to watch her get comfortable in a loving home and grow into a confident, silly, happy dog. We hope that she doesn't have to wait too long for the cozy home and loving mom or dad that she is so deserving of. 
(Not that it matters, but we called her "Rosie" while she was with us so she may respond to that). 

HW+ simply means the dog has tested positive for heart worms in our screening process. We utilize what is called the fast-kill method which means we place the dog on antibiotics for 30 days and then administer 3 injections in increments afterward. The cost to treat heart worms is rather steep. However, thanks to our generous donors, we are able to cover that cost for our adopters so long as they go to our veterinarian, Red Rocks Animal Center in Lakewood.


	Approved Applicants may make the adoption fee payment by clicking donate above. Partial adoption fees will not hold a dog.
	Dogs adopted with our rescue come with FREE training from #GoodPup to help you build strong bonds from the start!
	If upon meeting the dog of your choosing at an adoption event you find that you aren't a good match, your deposit will be refunded minus a 10% administration fee.
	Adoption fees include vaccines up until time of adoption, microchip, spay/neuter and 1st 30 days of free Pet insurance. We are not affiliated with Pet First pet insurance. (you have to sign up for the insurance or it will not go into effect). 
	Adopters can go to our vet for medical issues that may arise in 1st 3 days of adoption. 
	The dogs in our care are fostered in Colorado, Texas, and New Mexico. While all dogs are picked up during our scheduled times, sometimes transport dates change due to unforeseen circumstances.

animal.description: Anthony is a large Male chow mix. He is 7 years of age and has been neutered and has all shots. Anthony is a special needs dog with a condition called Cushing's Disease. He has a special prescription diet, and with daily exercise, his last liver panel and kidney checkup was favorable. This means with proper excersise and special diet he should not need any treatment for this condition. He currently lives with 3 other dogs, one male and two female. He has lived with cats before as well. He has always lived with elderly female owners, and can be protective if dogs get too close to his "mommy" , or when he is patrolling the fence. Anthony will spend hours a day curled at your feet, or if allowed will share the couch with you. He will spend lazy afternoons with you, or will stay by your side for miles on walks. When he goes with you for a drive, he likes to sit on the floor behind your seat. Ifyou are interested in Anthony please complete an application at Havendogrescue.org and his foster mom will call you to discuss. Anthony is currently on a struct diet and excercise and his blood panel is normal.

animal.description:
Meet Tinsel. Tinsel came to LWDR via a shelter in South Dakota. Her life prior to LWDR is unknown but now that she is safe, Tinsel is feeling a bit more comfortable. Tinsel is getting used to being in a home, being held and loved, possibly for the first time. 

Tinsel is thin although she eats well. I know I wish I had her metabolism.

Tinsel is being held and carried by her foster mom to show her that humans and touch are a good thing. Tinsel loves to know what is going on around her. When you least expect it, Tinsel will come up to you and kiss you. It is such a great feeling.

Tinsel is working on her house manners and leash training. Tinsel does not like to walk on a leash but if a leash is on her, she will follow when out for a walk.

Tinsel has been hiking and she likes the hike but she also likes to be carried. Tinsel is enjoying being spoiled.

Tinsel is often found on the loveseat enjoying the sunshine. Tinsel has stolen the heart of everyone she has met. 

 Tinsel is just over 7 lbs and 9 years old. She is spayed and UTD on all vaccinations and preventatives. 

Tinsel's adoption fee is $250 and she qualifies for the senior to senior discount.

animal.description:
Otis is a happy go lucky "pocket pit" boy who just wants a family to play with and be near! This sweetheart was seized from a cruelty case, but luckily is showing no long-term effects of being kept on a heavy logging chain 24/7 for the first 2 years of his life.

He LOVES everybody and is kid friendly (but could accidentally knock small children over when excited). He walks well on a harness leash, takes treats gently, and knows SIT. 

This guy is a shelter staff & volunteer favorite, so we're hoping he gets a loving family soon. One of our volunteers, Renee Hobbs, has been taking him on social outings/field trips so he gets to experience all the things he missed out on during the first 2 years of his life. He LOVES Sonic cheeseburgers, going for car rides, giving kisses, looking at himself in the mirror, and visiting local Hernando boutiques.

Otis is neutered, UTD on everything and is currently being treated for heartworms. 

To apply to adopt this smiling sweetheart, please visit this link https://www.jotform.com/hasadopt/pet-adoption-app or send an email to us at hasadoptions@gmail.com

The Pocket Pitbull, or Miniature Pitbull as this breed is sometimes known, is a more compact version of the well-known American Pitbull Terrier. A Pocket Bully is bred by crossing a Patterdale Terrier with an American Pitbull or American Staffordshire Terrier to produce a dog who is smaller in size, friendly, loyal, and loving.

Walker is an energetic and fun boy and he'd be perfect  for an active family. He knows "sit" and "lay down;" he needs training on leash walking but we're betting he'll pick that up quickly. Walker came into the shelter on Dec. 9 as a lost dog and his family has not found him. He is about 2 years old and weigh 60 pounds. He has  been neutered; he is up-to-date on vaccinations and will be microchipped upon adoption. Come meet him in Run 832 using ID#626385. Sadly he has tested positive for heartworms, but with treatment he should be good as new in no time. Please speak to your veterinarian regarding treatment options.

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

Ella is a year old. Her current weight is around 80 pounds.

The minimum donation for Ella is $475.00. This includes all of her vetting. If you are interested in Ella, please fill out an online application through our website.

We are currently only open by appointment only. Due to the recent pandemic, we are looking at the safety of our volunteers that are there to take care of the dogs. Only serious inquiries will be considered.

Then meet her at the shelter during adoption hours on Saturdays and Sundays 10 - 2pm. All members of the household need to meet the dog you are interested in. Vet records for any current or previous pets need to be provided. If all goes well, a home visit will be done prior to adoption.

animal.description:
Honey came to FOPAS absolutely scared of everything, and we mean everything.  We have no idea what had happened to this female Golden Retriever mix in her short life (estimated DOB of 10/2019) but it couldn't have been good.  Honey has now been in a loving and patient foster home for a few months and she is thriving!  Her foster dad says that from his office he can hear Honey and her canine foster sister running and playing up and down the hall.  She no longer cowers when she sees the leash to go outside; she'll come to the door, stand, and wait for the leash to be put on and the walk to begin.  She has even gained enough confidence to jump over the 3 foot fence, but so far she's just gone to the front yard.  Honey will need a somewhat quiet house and patient owners to allow her to continue to gain confidence and not to lose hope if there are any set backs.  She'll definitely need with a larger playful dog (or two) sibling to give her dog confidence and allow her to play.  No small children since the sounds of small children cause her anxiety.  Once you gain Honey's trust you'll have unlimited love and loyalty for years to come.  

If you are interested in Honey, please fill out an application here:
https://www.parkvilleshelter.com/adoption-application

animal.description:
Ladybird is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet her.

Ladybird is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption. 

Age: ~13 years old
Weight: ~13lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Working on it! Takes some time (10-30 minutes) to settle but overall doing great with her crate training.
Dog sociability: Prefers to be an only dog in the home but may have dog friends
Cat sociability: Not a match 
Kids: Unknown
Ideal home: Ladybird is looking for a home that is comfortable to take things slow with her as she warms up over time (with lots of high value snacks!) She prefers a quieter neighborhood so she doesn't have to pass by a bunch of other dogs or people while out on their walks as she can be a little nervous and barky. 

Ladybird is a cuddly, affectionate girl who wants nothing more than to curl up on your lap all day (with some long walks in between, of course). This Nap Queen prefers the finer things in life, like hot dogs, soft blankets, and your undivided attention. But don't underestimate her athletic prowess-she can walk for an hour and then bolt up four flights of stairs without batting an eye. She is a great apartment dog, but would also do well in a house with a yard she could sniff around in. She can be nervous when she meets new people, especially men, but can be won over with patience and lots of hot dogs. If you are looking for a sweet, charming senior dog to lounge around with, you may find the perfect match in Ladybird! 

Ladybird's adoption fee is sponsored thanks to a generous donor! She is spayed, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative. She will need a dental cleaning in the next year at the cost of her adopter. She also has a soft, round mass noted on her chest. Our vet suggests considering mass removal at time of her future dental.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
Meet Smiley! This 1 yr old, very handsome Golden-mixed fella has only been with us a few days, but we have learned a bit about him already. He is shy, but friendly and enjoys human attention. Many things are new to him, so patience as he learns about the world is a must. Smiley would most likely be an amazing companion for someone who loves to hike and/or run regularly. When he is first out on leash he pulls and is very strong. After a short while he settles down and is a great outing companion. We have not yet done formal dog-dog introductions but so far he has shown to be interested in other people and dogs while out on leash…but not reactive.

To date it is unknown how he would be with cats or young children under 7 years  of age.  As a result, he will need to go to a home where there are none.

?Update 01-16-21:  Smiley has shown us that he adores spending time with dogs. He has done quite nicely with and enjoys himself when with multiple dogs and breeds. He would be a great pack member in a home with a large yard where his humans are devoted to dogs, exercise, and proper/positive reinforcement  training methods.  Smiley is a very affectionate boy who loves belly rubs. He does need some obedience training when it comes to leash manners, jumping up on people and furniture, and has shown to be a counter surfer in his first home. He has also shown to be most comfortable around women, although he has learned to trust several men as the weeks have passed. Right now our boy is looking for a well matched foster or forever home. We still don’t know how he would do with kitties or small/young children.

GRCGLARescue adopts within the counties of Los Angeles, Ventura, Orange, Riverside, San Bernardino and San Diego. Because we do require pre-adoption screening and post-adoption follow-up, we cannot support adoptions outside of this service area. 

If you have a current application on file and would like to inquire about this dog, please email adoptions@grcglarescue.org. Otherwise, please make sure to complete the online adopter application found at http://www.grcglarescue.org/adopt before sending your inquiry.

He'd make a great hiking buddy. He knows how to sit and lie down and is working on other basic commands. He loves treats so he's making fast progress! 

Ham is good with other dogs and is completely indifferent and non-reactive to his senior foster sister's grumpiness. He is a strong guy and can play a little rough, so a home without small children would be best. Could this beautiful boy be right for your family?

PLEASE NOTE: A former DVBR family whose dog passed away recently reached out to us and they will be adopting Dolly. Their application came in among the initial flurry of applications. So, unless things fall through, Dolly is spoken for. Thank you all for your interest. Dolly had well over 100+ applications in less than 24 hours. But it looks like she has found her 'furever' home.

Dolly is a 3 month old puppy. She weighs about 3 or 4 lbs. and is about the cutest thing we've ever laid eyes on. Her favorite activity is looking for what kind of trouble she can start! The 14 yr. old female bichon she is currently living with in her foster home is very anxious for her to leave. Dolly's PERFECT family would have a fenced yard and another small, playful, young dog who won't think she's a pest. Ideally, someone would be around a lot, because this little baby LOVES attention. She LOVES to play and she plays hard. Dolly is not 100% house trained, but she's pretty darn close. She has an accident now & again, but she completely "gets it" and it's just a matter of time before the accidents are non-existent. Honestly, most of the time they are our fault and not hers. She's is the sweetest thing on Earth and we will be sad to see her go, but our little 14 yr. old bichon, Annie, will be throwing a party for all the geriatric bichons in the neighborhood! If you think you might make a great home for Dolly, step 1 would be to fill out an application. Once we have an application with a valid email address, we will get in touch. Do not call. We expect to be deluged with applications and will get to each person as quickly as possible. We will NOT place Dolly until AFTER Christmas. You can find an application on our website: www.dvbr.org and our email address for questions is bichonrescue@gmail.com

animal.description:
Please contact JoEllen (sagdinfo@gmail.com) for more information about this pet.Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **
Hope is a sweet 8-year-old Great Dane. She was abandoned by her previous owners at one of the most horrific kill shelters in the Rio Grande Valley. She was suffering from extreme malnutrition but has since achieved a healthy weight while in foster care. She now becomes very talkative if her foster mom is late with dinner! Hope lives in a foster home with other Great Danes and she interacts nicely with them - although she does not put up with any nonsense from the energetic younger Great Danes.
Hope did test positive for ehrlichia which is a bacteria infection caused by a tick bite and she completed a 30-day course of doxycycline.
Please understand you are committing to providing a good home for her entire life (up to 15+ years or more.)
You must be committed to housebreaking, age-appropriate enrichment and exercise, leash training, grooming needs, and positive socialization.
Her adoption fee is $250. This includes her spay surgery, rabies vaccination, Nobivac Canine 1-DAPP vaccination, Nobivac Intra-Trac 3 vaccination, Drontal Plus, Tri-Heart Plus Chewable Tablet, IDEXX SNAP 4Dx Plus Test, 24PetWatch microchip, leash and collar, and a trial offer for 24PetWatch Pet Insurance.
Please be aware that puppies and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.
Please ensure your application is complete before submitting. We do verify property ownership, landlord references, apartment/HOA restrictions, veterinary references, and criminal histories.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@gmail.com.
** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and adults dogs are tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and opportunity to enroll in a 30-day trial of pet insurance.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time from the Austin area.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Michelle at mhunt@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Roscoe
Estimated Breed : Retriever Mix
Approximate Age: 2 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 45 lbs
Currently Living at: Foster
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Roscoe is a special dog. His foster reports that he is anxious to trust and love and has quickly adopted and blossomed into an affectionate and loyal companion. He is a highly intelligent, active and sensitive and loves his belly rubs!!! While he is still practicing walking on a leash - he will need a fenced in back yard (no apts/condos). He is ready for his forever home and would enjoy an active, stimulating environment with a yard to play in.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
MUST BE ADOPTED TOGETHER!

Sabyn, Great Pyrenees, 8 years old (possibly a little older), Female
Wovey, Lab Mix, 7-8 years old, Female

Wovey and Sabyn's guardian passed away and they ended up in a high kill shelter, next in line for euthanasia because nobody wanted to care for these neglected girls anymore. Their only family is gone, forever. 

Sabyn is a very mellow female Great Pyrenees, 8 yrs old. She looks like she is twice that age from the neglect and depression. She has spondylosis and is arthritic. Nothing can really be done about this except to ease her pain with meds the rest of her life. She is currently on medications that are working well, and are not costly. She might enjoy Aqua-therapy or acupuncture if given the opporrunity. 

Wovey is her 7-8 yr old lab mix sister. She had 2 large tumors removed when our southern rescue partner saved her. To the vet's surprise, both were benign! She is just "lumpy" and has small benign tumors pop up from time to time. 
 
They seem to be fine with dogs and cats, Sabyn likes kids, Wovey isn't sure. 

Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England.

animal.description:
Hello my name is Pooka and I am looking for a HOME!

I am a one and half year old 60 pound active Lab & Pittie mix who was adopted as a pup and now due to no fault of my own I'm back at the rescue.

My story started at the scary pound where I was dumped as a baby and this nice rescue got me outta there.
They sent me to their trainer and I was pretty much a perfect pup!

I got adopted but I started showing some minor fixable issues so the rescue sent their amazing trainer out to show my humans what to do.
They felt it was "too much" and ignored the trainers advice and went to a different trainer who didn't give the right instructions. 
Then they decided it was just too much trouble and sent me back here, I just wish humans would understand that we doggos are living and feeling beings and not a pair of shoes that you are tired of wearing or have become uncomfortable or what have you.

The rescue sent me BACK to the trainer and I am doing so much better now!

I love to go on long walks and hikes and adventures too!
The perfect home for me will be someone who can give me the structure I need so I can continue to be a good and balanced dog.
I'm good with other dogs but I can be a bit dominant so the perfect place would be if I'm the only dog or with a balanced male doggo.
I'm house and crate trained and very smart and very motivated!
Sorry but no little dogs, cats or kids for me, adults only home please!

If you think we are a good match please go to www.bulliesandbuddies.com and fill out an application to ADOPT me ok?!

I am in the Southern CA area-sorry but my rescue does NOT adopt out of state

I am an UNDERDOG because....

I am a hound mix! Hound breeds are very prominent in the rural south and usually the first to be euthanized at the shelter due to the overpopulation of this breed.

Not compatible with: Dogs

Not tested with:

Kids, Cats

Hi, I'm Bernie! I'm a sweet and serious pup with beautiful puppy dog eyes. I'm a major snuggle bug even though I'm 65 lbs -- I act like a lap dog! I am working on walking nicely on a leash but I'm a smart pup so I'm certain to learn quickly with some consistent training. I can get aggravated with other dogs so I need to be the only dog in a home. I'm just a grumpy guy sometimes and I like my space! I also get spooked with loud noises sometimes. If I had a family who can work on my leash skills and build my confidence, that would improve. I love people more than anything else and will follow you around all day to get pets and snuggles.

I can't wait to find my forever home where I can share all the love I've got to give!

Adoption Application:

http://bit.ly/adoptrdr

Adoption Application:
http://bit.ly/adoptrdr

Foster Application: http://bit.ly/fosterapprdr

Adoption Process: In order to adopt, we require an adoption application. After you submit an application, if you pass the screening, we will contact you to schedule a phone interview. We will call your references, including your veterinarian and landlord (when appropriate). We will also conduct a home visit. After these steps are complete, you will be approved to adopt a dog. Please note this process takes 1-2 weeks so applications submitted when you are ready to bring a dog home within that time frame. You can meet our adoptable dogs at events, however, we cannot guarantee that dogs at events do not have pre-approved applicants meeting them there as well, so the application is the best way to start the process.

Mission Statement: Forever true to "The Underdog", Rural Dog Rescue is dedicated to saving the lives of dogs in shelters who are often overlooked for adoption or rescue. We save the dogs who are at most risk of being euthanized: the hounds, the black dogs, the seniors, the sick and the broken. We make a commitment to reserve a minimum of 50% of the dogs we save to The Underdog. Root For The Underdog!

Rural Dog Rescue's home base is in Washington, DC. We adopt to the Washington, DC metropolitan area to include Maryland and Northern Virginia.

We support several high kill shelters that euthanize in 72 hours and whose kill rate is 70% or higher in rural areas of Virginia, West Virginia, North and South Carolina. Rural Dog Rescue also helps dogs in need in Washington, DC and Maryland.

We are 100% volunteer and foster based and no salaries are paid. 100% of your donation and adoption fee goes to helping the dogs and cats of Rural Dog Rescue.

Although we try to be as accurate as possible, Rural Dog Rescue cannot guarantee the breed or full-grown adult size of any of the dogs or puppies in its care. Because many of these dogs were found as strays or are the result of irresponsible, unplanned breeding, we do not know the dog's exact background and can only list breed and size by our best educated guess. If exact breed and size are important to you, please consider adopting a dog from a specific breed rescue. Our goal is for our dogs to be adopted by people who will love and care for them forever for who they are - no matter what breed and size they turn out to be!

All dogs go to their new homes spayed or neutered, up to date on all shots, dewormed (although a second deworming may be required), started on heartworm and flea and tick preventative and sometimes microchipped.

animal.description:
Rosie is an energetic, active lady ready to make a special someone the center of her world. 
Rosie was abandoned weeks away from giving birth at a high kill shelter by her human dad. She has been a diligent mother to her seven puppies, despite being ostensibly a puppy herself. Rosie needs someone that will teach her that humans can be trusted and to teach her how to be a good doggie citizen.
Rosie is very smart, and requires stimulation and exercise to be her best self. She is very curious, and very loving.  She wants to be by your side as much as possible and loves to give affection.
Rosie is a sweet, sweet girl but no one taught her basic manners. She’s working on not jumping and her leash behavior. She has shown some minor resource guarding which with a little training can be brought under control. Because she has so much energy, she would do best in a home without very young children or senior pets.
She’s got the cutest tall ears and beautiful coloring. Rosie is about a year old and ~45 pounds. She is heartworm negative, spayed, and ready! If you want an affectionate, sweet, attentive adventure buddy, and you love an underdog, then Rosie is the gal for you.

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at

michelel@k-9lifesavers.org

You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.

Dog's Name: Sugar

Estimated Breed : Bulldog Mix

Approximate Age: 2 years

Approximate Weight: approx. 45 lbs

Currently Living at: Boarding

Adoption Fee: $375

DOG'S DESCRIPTION

Sugar is a sweet momma dog waiting for a loving forever home. She loves affection, and is super sweet. She is currently at a foster home and is friendly with the foster family dog. Foster mom says she is a really pleasant easy dog to have around. She does not always know her strength when giving love, so best with kids over 10. The foster family adores her!

Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.

Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.

Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org

Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!

For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.

Please "like" our
Facebook Page
for the most current events and new dogs.

Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Welcome Sully to Battle for the Bully! Sully is a year old and comes to us already vetted and ready for adoption. His foster mom writes the below:
"Sully is the happiest, goofiest, most handsome Pitbull-Boxer mix who is looking for a home as loving as he is. He loves to cuddle (all 65 lbs of him) and be near his people. He is most fond of his “breakfast” (his three meals each day) and his daily walks. He plays very well with other dogs at doggy day care, which he attends 3-4x a week.

Sully loves to sleep with his humans on the bed, but is also kennel trained and will sleep in his kennel. He is fully house-trained. He knows many words (sit, lay, come, wait, car ride, walk, outside, shake, breakfast, toy, cookie, treat, etc.). The one word that he has not mastered yet is “drop.” He can be stubborn, and will occasionally not give up a food item if he finds it on a walk.  Sully isn’t scared of much…except the vacuum. He hasn’t quite figured out what this very loud, object is that mom and dad push around the living room.

Sully will live best in a home where can spend a lot of time with his people. He would most enjoy a home where he has a fenced in yard to play, and where he is regularly attended to. He would also like an active family that likes to go on walks or hikes.  He still has puppy tendencies and is still learning to not pull too hard on the leash. Keeping him busy and stimulated is important.
If you are looking for a sweet, happy guy with the biggest heart, look no further -  Sully is your main man. He’ll be loyal ‘til the end and deserves the same in return"

Please understand we match our dogs based on temperament/needs, not physical appearance. If you are unable to accommodate the needs of Sully, please do not apply. We would like his transition to be as seamless as possible. 

Please review our website and review our FAQ's before applying. Sully will not be placed in a home with kids under the age of 13 years due to his playful nipping, no exceptions. Link to website below:

https://www.battleforthebully.org/

animal.description:
Senior Hearts Rescue and Renewal is the only licensed senior dog rescue organization in Western Pennsylvania. We do not have a shelter or a public facility. ALL of our dogs reside in foster homes in the greater Pittsburgh, PA area. 

We are a 100% volunteer organization. Please respect our volunteers' time. If a dog is listed on PetFinder, he/she IS available for adoption. We cannot reply to messages, phone calls, and emails about a dog until we have received, reviewed, and approved an adoption application. 

Our ADOPTION application is found at www.seniorhearts.org Completing this application is the first step in our adoption screening process. You MUST complete the application in its entirety in order to be considered as a potential adopter.  Please select "More About Us" for further details on our adoption requirements.  You can meet a dog ONLY after we have completed our adoption approval process.

If you are looking at the dog below, it most certainly means the dog is available for adoption. We look forward to receiving your application in hopes that you are able to meet our adoption requirements and provide this dog with a loving furever home.

And now a word from our sweet Cookie...

I will tell you a bit about myself. I am 11 years young. I could almost fit in your pocket weighing only 8 pounds. I'm a shy girl. I don't like lots of commotion and new things scare me. But once I am comfortable I am easy going. I'm not a needy girl. I enjoy my independence.

I like to go on short walks and explore the great outdoors. I do require a fenced yard. I do want to have a doggie sibling. He will help me feel comfortable.   

I do appreciate getting lots of love and snuggles from humans too. After all I am the sweetest Cookie you may ever meet.

I am looking for a calm adult only home. I can be adopted within a two-hour radius of Pittsburgh, PA. If you are interested in giving me a furever home, you must first complete the adoption application at www.seniorhearts.org

xoxo
Cookie

animal.description:
Hi! I’m Conan. Kind of a serious name for a goofball like me. I should’ve been named Smiley or something. I was picked up on a busy Highway one day; the person who picked me up witnessed someone throwing me out of their truck. Made me feel like a piece of trash. But that’s okay because the cool folks at ARFhouse took me in and It’s like I’m a brand new dog!! 

I am a sweet, young Doberman; approximately 2 years old and I weigh 73 lbs. BIG BOY! I love to play, get all the belly rubs and snuggle with my favorite humans. I get along fine with other dogs but would prefer to be the only dog in the home. I want all the attention for myself. Because of my size and energy level, I would not be suitable for an apartment; I need a large, fenced yard so I can run and play whenever I want! 

The fee to adopt Conan is $200.00; this includes spay/neuter, deworming, vaccinations and a microchip. If you are interested in adopting Conan, please visit our website. www.arfhouse.org and fill out an adoption application. 

**Please Note: Conan is currently located at our facility in Sherman, Texas. Adoptions are by-appointment only; if you would like to meet Conan, please fill out an application on our website. Once we have your application, our Adoption Coordinator will follow up with you ASAP with any questions she may have, or to set up a meet-and-greet.

animal.description:
Dee is in a foster home, and is currently not at the shelter. Please find info below on how to adopt her, thanks. 

Imagine - a chilly winter evening, you and me, snuggled up on the couch, watching our fav Netflix show. Or, you've had a rough day at work, but you come home to my smiling face and wagging tail, and now you've got a huge smile on your face too.....our life together would be amazing! I'm a silly, curious, sometimes zoomy girl who's excited about life. At eight years young, I'm sprightly and acrobatic and always up for training and games - I'm food motivated and love to learn. Sleeping in bed with my foster parent is great, maybe you'll let me sleep with you too? Hanging out in my crate is cool, but my foster parent doesn't require me to stay in it when they're gone because I'm such a good girl I never ever get into things I shouldn't!

I thrive on structure and a regular schedule that includes training. So far I've learned come', sit', let's go this way' and we're working on touch'. I've got house training down. While I almost never bark when the doorbell rings, I will warn you when there's a squirrel intruder in the back yard! Dee is learning to relax more while on the leash - sometimes other dogs and squirrels especially can be distracting to her!
Here's what I need from you, my forever family to be - plenty of prior dog experience and dog behavior knowledge, a home without any other pets (I really prefer humans to other dogs) or young children, and a quiet neighborhood. Absolutely nothing would make me happier than a home for the holidays!

HOW TO ADOPT - Please fill out a Dog Adoption Application, available at http://www.seattle.gov/animalshelter/forms.htm and email it to the Seattle Animal Shelter Foster Dog Program at adoptionreview@gmail.com.

IMPORTANT NOTE: Many of our dogs will receive numerous applications, and the Seattle Animal Shelter asks for your patience during the process of finding the very best match. If you have questions about this dog that have not been answered above, please contact us at sasfosterdogs@gmail.com. If you would like to arrange to meet this dog, you must submit an adoption application. Thank you!

animal.description: ROSIE is an 11 year old Shih Tzu mix who doesn’t act her age. She is very active, a little anxious and nobody can believe that she is 11! Rosie belong to a 93-year-old woman who passed away. We can’t imagine Rosie living with a 93 yr old! Rosie loves her walks and will pull our volunteers around the park. She is reactive with other dogs and was the only dog in her previous home. She is not cat compatible and would do best as the only pet to soak up all of your love and attention. Rosie adores children and Although she might be a bit of a handful with wee little ones, kids 7 and up would be ideal. Rosie would do best with a fenced yard due to her reactivity with other animals – it would give her a safe place to go potty in between walks. Rosie was very well cared for in her previous home. She had blood work done in July which showed some elevated liver values. She is currently on a liver supplement - Denamarin (over-the-counter) which she takes every morning in a pill pocket. Rosie has been vaccinated, spayed, microchip and heartworm tested negative. Adoption $200. If you or the family Rosie is looking for, please fill out an application www.companimals.org.

animal.description:
Cookie
Update 12/14/2020: Cookie has come back to us due to the passing of both of her owners. She is now 4 years old (Estimated DOB 8-10 / 2016). Cookie is house trained. She is a very lovable and a sweet girl. She is a bit of a chunky monkey weighing in at 62 pounds. She is very treat driven and she can't help that she loves her Blue Health Bars and Sizzlers. Cookie does love to play and run. She can be a bit rambunctious around smaller dogs just because of her energy levels. She has been tested with kids 5 and up and she is very submissive and loves to bump noses and give kisses. Cookie is looking for a new home with other playful dogs so she won't be lonely. She should fit in with an active family or person.
Original: Cookie is an adorable lab mix who was found and not claimed. She is black with speckled toes and white chest. Cookie also has a stub tail. We don't know what happened there. She is about 4-6 months old and she is a chunky 35 pounds. Cookie loves to play with other dogs and kids. She will need to learn her manners and wil most likely need a little help with house training. Don't be surprised if she chews a little as well. If your wanting a fun pup in your life that will keep you on your toes, this is your girl! Date of Intake: 2/20/17, 12/15/2020
Cookie is located at Maumelle Animal Services, 425 Cogdell Drive, Maumelle Arkansas. Open M-F 10-5, Sat. 12-4:30. Phone: 501-851-6219. Email us at Dogs@maumellefoa.org for more information on foster dogs. Online adoption applications available at www.Maumellefoa.org. Our adoption fee is $80. Included in the fee is shots, sterilization, microchip, dogs are given a dewormer at time of intake, placed on monthly flea/tick preventative, if heartworm negative then they are placed on heartworm preventative, if heartworm positive then they are treated once an adoption finalized.
Please note regarding the application to adopt: Personal references, landlord reference and veteranarian references / vetting history will be checked. All past and current pets must have been or must be up to date on vaccines and given heart worm preventative unless otherwise indicated by your veteranarian. If you use multiple vet clinics, please include them all.
Find Maumelle Friends of the Animals on Facebook!

animal.description:
Birthday: 11/17/2015
Pet ID: 131037

Asia is more than ready for her happily ever after!

This exuberant lady unfortunately came in as a neglect case back in November. Her skin was all types of messed up due to Demodectic mange. Through the wonders of TLC and veterinary care, Asia now looks as good as new!

Asia is around 5 years of age. However, she still has lots of puppy energy and reminds us of Wonder Woman because of the super strength she possesses. She will definitely need a strong handler equipped for teaching her basic manners and leash walking skills. Asia also LOVES squeaky toys and showing them off to her hooman friends during playtime.

The only thing we are still working on getting under control healthwise with Asia is her extreme happy tail. The tip of her tail was completely raw when she came into our care, and she would wag it so hard that it would fling blood everywhere. We currently have it wrapped to promote healing and have placed an e-collar on her to keep her from picking at the bandage, which seems to be working!

If you’d like to give Asia the loving home she so deserves, then give us a call at 804-991-3200 to set up a meet-and-greet today!

If you have any questions about our adoptable pets, we can be reached by phone at 804-991-3200 or by email at pganimals@princegeorgecountyva.gov.

Be sure to check out our Facebook and Instagram pages at Facebook.com/pganimals and Instagram.com/pganimals!

animal.description: Hobbes is a happy, active and highly cuddly dog.   He loves curling up by the wood stove and chewing on his doggy toys.  He is crate trained, house trained, rides well in a car with a barrier (as he would prefer to be in your lap), loves to play ball, tucks himself to sleep and has attended basic obedience classes.  He knows sit, wait, come, lay-down, roll-over, will heel when he isn't full of beans especially if you have a treat motivator.  Hobbes will let you touch his paws, cut his nails, and clean his ears while enjoying the attention and rubs.  He has been in a foster home with other dogs he wants to be the only animal in the home. He is a beautiful and loving brindle boy with a mischievous side about one year of age and loves people. Hobbes is very loving and He snuggles and tucks his nose into your arm when next to you and when lays behind you in a chair, with his head he'll place it gently on your thigh. If you're on the sofa and looking for an oversized lap dog, he's your boy. Because of his size he'd be best in a home with older children. Hobbs's best home would be where he can be near his humans and have access to toys and chews so he can entertain himself.  If you can commit to a one-dog home with a highly loving and loyal boy please consider Hobbes. These precious puppies and dogs were released to our rescue or were all pulled from kill shelters and are looking for a forever home where they can love on a family to call their own. The faster we can find forever homes for these sweeties, the more Winnies Legacy Rescue can save. We often pull black dogs as they have the least chance to make it out. Please please share this posting so we can network to make a difference in their life. If you'd like to adopt, in the adoption fee, we make zero profit. It covers pull fee from the shelter, transportation to our Charlotte, VT location, vetting, paperwork to get them across state lines, shots, deworming, food and more. (Please do not fill out an application if you're not able to come to VT to adopt) You can also help by liking, following and sharing our f.b. page Winnies Legacy Canine Rescue. Our web page is https:www.winnieslegacy.com if you would like an adoption application. If you'd like to foster to assist us in saving lives like these darlings.

Chino was an owner surrender, we were told that they could not keep Chino any longer because they had a new baby and Chino jumps up. 

Chino does jump up, but just needs some work to stop that behavior. He does know how to sit, shake, high five and lay down. 

Chino is particular with dogs, he is a very dominant dog and likes to be the boss. He did fine with the smaller female dog and the larger sized medium dog he was introduced too as well. Both females were afraid of him, since he is so dominant. But he ultimately did try to play with the larger girl. 

I think once he is neutered and once his testosterone is out of his system that he would do better with male dogs, but that is just a guess.

He is absolutely wonderful with people and loves attention, he is housebroken and he will make a wonderful addition to a new family.

animal.description:
Bart (Snoop) was surrendered to a local shelter when his owner could no longer care for him. He is just about a year old and very much still a puppy. Bart is underweight at about 70 pounds and will be a big boy once he fills out. He is a typical GSD that loves to follow his person around. Bart likes playing and chewing his toys along with playing tug. He is intelligent and picks up on new commands quickly. Bart is very playful, and is still learning boundaries. He can be mouthy when being handled, especially around his head. His foster dad is working on teaching him to move away instead of becoming mouthy. Bart would do best in a home with older dog savvy children. He is a strong boy on leash but does well being walked on a harness. Bart is very good in his crate and his adopter should continue to utilize one to give him down time and relax. Training will be necessary for Bart to continuing socializing and work on basic commands. Bart has never lived with other dogs and while he is not dog aggressive, he would do best as an only dog. He is not confident or socialized with other dogs. Bart will thrive in a home willing to provide him mental and physical stimulation - after all German Shepherds are working dogs! 

The application is our first step and we will let you know as soon as it arrives. Adoption fee includes: spay or neuter, all shots, heart worm testing, fecal test and microchip..

Many questions can be answered by going to www.gsrescue1.org

animal.description:
Hi my name is Cherokee! I am a sweet boy - who loves attention and loves to be loved. I am also a big, stubborn blockhead. I like to learn, but sometimes it is much more fun to not listen immediately, so I will need a family that will be firm and set expectations from the get go. I am good in my crate and am learning to slow down my eating and not inhale or guard in any way.  I am active, but like most pitties, am not the biggest fan of the cold...big wusses we are.  I am good with other dogs, but I do play rough and will need a playmate that is able to be tolerant but correct when need be. My new family is going to get a fun, happy guy who is really ready for a stable, loving home that will make sure I mind my manners. 

ADOPTION FEE: $200 (All MVPC dogs are heartworm-tested, completely vetted, spayed/neutered, microchipped, crate-trained and house-trained)

A $100 hold fee is required for approved applications and will be applied to the full adoption fee at the time of the home visit. 
ADOPTER: Dog experience
BIRTHDAY: Estimated 1-2 years
FENCE: Required (an electric fence is not an acceptable form of containment)
DOGS: Yes
CATS: Unknown, but can test
KIDS: Yes, over 5 please

INQUIRIES: ALL inquiries begin with a submitted adoption application, which is found on our website, www.miamivalleypitcrew.com. We do not adopt to individuals under the age of 25. We prefer male/female dog pairings unless both already reside in the home. 

DO NOT: USE THE PETFINDER CONTACT/ADOPT BUTTONS--we are unable to monitor those and you will not receive a response. 

PLEASE NOTE: We are volunteer based and a home visit is required; we have a two-hour adoption radius from Kettering, OH for our adult dogs and 75 miles for our puppies. Exceptions for our ADULT dogs only, though rare, may be made on a case-by-case basis but we must be able to do a home visit. Thank you for your understanding!

animal.description:
Meet Miss Tea Pot a 1 year old Boxer/Terrier mix (breed is just a guess) who weighs in at 42 lbs. Miss Tea Pot is a very sweet and loving girl who is energetic and playful and LOVES to play with the other dog in her foster home. Miss Tea Pot has great manners and her foster mom describes her as an "old soul". Miss Tea Pot would be happiest in a home where her people are not gone all day and have another young and playful dog. Miss Tea Pot is not fostered with children, so for this reason, if there are children in her forever home they should be 8 yrs and up. Miss Tea Pot is not suited to first time dog owners. Miss Tea Pot is not suited to apartment/condo living. She is spayed, microchipped, up-to-date on vaccines, and preventatives and eager to find a family to love!

The adoption fee for this dog is $350 which includes routine vetting and spay/neuter.

***Please note that our first step is submitting an application (it does not commit you in any way but allows us to discuss with you if you and the dog are a good fit). In addition, an important step in approving adoption applicants is to complete a vet check. Vetting of current and past pets is very important to us, thus we will be speaking with the vet(s) listed on your application to ensure that your current and previous pet(s) are kept up to date on vaccines (including rabies), spayed or neutered, maintained on appropriate monthly preventatives and examined annually by your vet.***

If you would like to meet Miss Tea Pot, please fill out our online application by clicking HERE and then email Kim at KLarimerLovepaws@gmail.com

If you are viewing this on PetFinder or other venue, please go to our website at www.lovepawspg.org

animal.description: Hi! My name is Kenny! I was rescued by the wonderful people at Big Dog Ranch from a hoarding house in Puerto Rico before arriving here at the ranch. I am a good dog but sometimes I'm not the best listener and I tend to do what I want most of the time, probably because I've never lived in a home with rules and structure. But don't let that deter you! I'm a great pick for an experienced owner who knows how to help a pup like me become the very best dog that he can be. I am a medium energy dog who absolutely loves every human that I meet! I like to play with other dogs, but can be selective with who I choose to play with sometimes. I think I would be happiest in an adult-only household and I would love nothing more than to find a home that has a great big yard for me to run around and play in. I will probably be protective of my new space and new people, because I've never had such nice things in my life before! I think I'd be happiest living a quieter lifestyle with my new family, and while I may be protective, I can also be friendly when meeting new people. I would definitely benefit from continued obedience training, but I do appear to be relatively potty-trained at this time. I am not a huge fan of walking on my leash yet, but I just did it for the very first time in my entire life when I arrived here at the ranch, so please be patient with me!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Kahlua! I was rescued by the wonderful people at Big Dog Ranch from a hoarding house in Puerto Rico before arriving here at the ranch. I am a very timid little girl and tend to be very cautious when meeting new people, probably due to the unstable environment from which I came. Because I'm so scared, I tend to be protective of my space since I'm afraid you're going to take it away from me. I'd be a good fit for an experienced dog owner who is familiar with working with dogs who are fearful due to past trauma. I like to play with other dogs, but can be selective with who I choose to play with sometimes. I think I would be a good family pet, but I would prefer a home with children over the age of 12 who can be aware of my anxiety and help me learn to push through it with loving kindness. I do think there's a possibility that I may be able to live peacefully in a home with a feline companion though! I would be happiest living a quiet lifestyle in my new home and could see myself being very happy in a range of home environments, from a large home with a big yard to a smaller apartment. I could benefit from continued training, but I do appear to have some handle on potty-training. I am very fearful of the leash and will need an adopter who is willing to show me that leash-walking can be fun for me!

animal.description:
* MEDICAL SPECIAL NEEDS - DISTEMPTER SURVIVOR *
Scarlett is a most precious resident at Satchels, she is adored by all who see her smile. Scarlett had distemper as a puppy which has resulted in life long neurological issues. That means nothing to her, Scarlett is a spunky heartthrob. She's quirky, loves other animals and people. With her condition she has a special way of communicating and is always up for a chatter. In her previous home we were told she was picked on by the other pups but her she has come out of her shell and she is running with the best of them! A bigger, older puppy would be the perfect playmate for her as she sometimes plays with her mouth. An adult only home would be best for Scarlett since her talking can sometimes be a little rambunctious. She does require help with potty training and needs a home where someone is home most of the time. She hasn't caught the hang of how to sit or those basics yet, but she will come to you quicker than anyone you know and listens very well to no! Once you see her spinning with joy for you, you won't want to spend another day without her! Scarlett is 2 years old and weighs approximately 45 lbs. For an appointment to meet her, please submit the adoption application (no commitment) found on our website, www.satchelslastresort.org, and an adoption counselor will be in touch.

animal.description: Say Hello to the Boba Tea Pups! All these precious little ones want for Christmas is a forever home, and at around 4 months old, they are ready to make your holidays Merry and Bright! They came to Labs and More without mom or dad so we don't know what all they are mixed with, but we think they look like Labrador/Doberman Pinscher mixes and that they are on track to be medium to large dogs when they are all grown up. Matcha is looking for a family that understands the time, patience, and energy needed to raise a young pup. We require all puppy adopters to provide training that includes: house training, basic training, leash training, and socialization. Additionally, this cutie is going to need proper exercise, mental stimulation, and your attention and love to grow up to be the best companion. We do not allow our dogs or puppies to sleep or live outside; they must be incorporated into your family and be made a priority in your life. In return, you will have the most loving and loyal family member you could ask for. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting a puppy, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! Please note that processing time for applications is currently three to four weeks. We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
*	Buddy is estimated to be almost 7 years old! Estimated to be a hound mix. This special BOY has special adoption needs!
	o	Buddy is NOT for the person or family who has a vision of a perfect dog on Day 1. 
*	From our perspective, Buddy is joyful, exuberant, intelligent, agile, active, and affectionate! 
	o	Something we are confident Buddy will display in time - once you get to know one another. 
*	Everyone has a story... Buddy's includes him being rescued from his solitary life on a chain, abandoned again to be saved by our Rescue finding himself in a very different environment he's ever experienced!
*	Understandably, Buddy is slow to trust humans but when you gain his trust, he shows his heart to be joyful and fun-loving companion!
*	From the perspective of a tenured volunteer who spends extra time with Buddy (often off site): 
	o	Buddy enjoys long walks where he can sniff and explore, get needed exercise, and stop for ear rubs and hugs. 
	o	He does zoomies in the yard, explores the shrubs, and enjoys snuggles during quiet time in the house. 
	o	Buddy interacts very well with our volunteers' calm, well-balanced dog after a slow introduction. 
	o	He is friendly as he meets people and usually passes other dogs calmly. 
*	When introduced at the Rescue, he can be excitable when he meets some dogs and people. But he learns quickly as he is treat-motivated to sit, stay, lie down, and come on command!
*	Taking into account Buddy's trust issues, he is ISO a furever scenario where: 
	o	His person/people (or family with older, calm children) are dog savvy and can provide consistent training.
	o	His potential adopters would be willing to visit him several times before adoption. We ask you to meet him during a walk with a volunteer.
	o	His person/people would be patient and give Buddy time to decompress as he learns to trust you.
*	If Buddy tugs at your heart, call the Rescue TODAY to make your initial appointment to meet Buddy, 803-802-0902.If you wish to meet me, please call the Humane Society of York County at (803)-802-0902 to schedule an appointment. Adoption consultations are by appointment only.

Hi, I'm Danny. I'm a chihuahua and don't I know it! I love to curl up under blankets, play with my toys and snuggle with my foster family.
I'm not too trusting of new people but hey, someone's gotta protect the family, might as well be me. I'm little but I'm loyal and strong. That's what my foster mom says and I have to agree with her. I will be best in a home with no young children under the age of 13.

I got the best foster family. They keep me cozy warm in sweaters and blankets. I get yummy food and they really like me. But I'd really like to move on now to the place I'll be the rest of my life.
So my foster mom thought I should write you all here to see if there's a family out there that loves real handsome chihuahuas that will be fiercely loyal and very loving. If so that's me, Danny.
