animal.description: Hello! My name is Mack, I am believed to be 15 years old, but that number is a lie! You'd never believe it when you see me. I was an owner surrender at no fault of my own, coming in on October 29. I've spent my time here with the ladies getting used to them and my new routine. Some would call me an old man stuck in his way, but I promise this old dog can learn some new tricks. Some days I can be ""hot n cold"" meaning, some days I love to have attention and loved on, other days, please don't touch me with a 10 ft pole. I get along with all other animals but a meet and greet would be best. It would also be best that I be in a home with no children. I need a rather calm house that will just let me lounge as I please. I LOVE going on car rides and sometimes even find myself falling asleep. I'm a special dog, that needs special love. Some what like a sour patch kid, first their sour, then their sweet. If you find yourself interested in me, please come at the shelter at 2603472563 or via Facebook messenger.

animal.description:
The best part of rescuing a dog is being able to provide a happy home for the imperfectly perfect souls of this world! To give the "underdog" a chance at a beautiful life. They sometimes come with the very best stories and make the very best companions. 

Let me introduce you to Lolita and her mom, Beylita. They are two of the sweetest Chihuahua mixes- who weren't always this way. Due to their skin condition, they have run into not the nicest of people in the past and it took a while for these sweet girls to learn trust. They have been in an amazing foster home for the past few months learning what love is. What it is to always have full bellies, furry friends and hooman friends. Love is all around them now and they reciprocate it! These girls are now so amazing and loving, greeting you with bounces, tail wags, tongues out and bellies up! They look to be friends with everyone and every dog! A little timid at first but once they feel comfortable, it is all fun and love thereafter! They are fearless and love to be around dogs of all sizes, and are not afraid to give off a corrective growl toward another doggo when they feel uncomfortable. It never goes past that-- they just say "give me space" and trot along in the other direction, tail wagging! Now full of life and confidence, they can be yappy when excited but simmer down quickly. They are both crate and house trained and ready for a start to their new lives. Mom and daughter have lived all of their lives together and rely on eachother for comfort, so they will need to be adopted together. They are so tiny that two dogs is no different than having one-- double the love without taking up much more space! 

Lolita is estimated at 1-2 years of age and a CHUNK, weighing in at 13 lbs! Her momma is slightly smaller (also a chunky monkey), weighing in at approx 10 lbs. They both suffer from alopecia. We initially believed it was mange or some sort of skin infection but after medical treatment and different treatment approaches, we have learned that it is what it is. This is who they are and how they will always look-- nothing short of BEAUTIFUL! Convenia injections very temporarily make a difference. You will see some hair growth, but it quickly goes back to the adorable patchy look. It's very adorable, if you ask me! Beylita's chest and head are smooth like a baby's bottom! Their foster momma has also been working on nail trims and slowly cutting back at the overgrown nails they first started with-- huge progress!

If you are ready to fill your heart with so much love, please don't sleep on these two diamonds in the ruff! Apply here to bring them home https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/19764/generic or email cynthia@threelittlepittiesrescue.org if you have an application on file.

Their combined adoption fee for both is $900 and includes all vaccines (DHPP & booster, Bordatella, Rabies), spay microchip, multiple dewormings, heartworm treatment, flea and heartworm preventative with 2 month of heartworm preventative for each after adoption, a high quality nylon Martingale collar, a 30 day trial of pet insurance, and transport from TX to the PNW.

**APPLICATION REQUIRED FOR A RESPONSE**

animal.description:
Dog Name: COLBY

Sex: Male

Age: 8 years old

Weight: 95 lbs

Medical: He needs daily medication it will be approximately $80 a month. Colby will not need HW medication for a full year! He has had the pro heart 12 shot! 

Housebroken: Yes

Crate trained: Yes, will whine initially then settles right down

Good in the car: Yes! Just lays there and hangs out. 

Good on a leash: If a prong collar is use, yes. He will pull hard otherwise.

Energy level: Low to medium. Depends on the day and time.

Need a fenced in yard: Not necessarily. He would be fine with leashed bathroom breaks and a short walk.

Dog Friendly: Yes! 

If yes, does your foster need another dog in its adoptive homes? No

Cat Friendly? He is curious about them, but if you tell him to leave it, he will not bother the cat

Kid Friendly: Yes! Lived with a 4 year old. Does great with my 5 month old, however he needs to be supervised.

If yes, what's the youngest child you'd recommend they be placed with? any age, as long as there is supervision at all times.

Special traits that make your foster special or that we need to know about them?

Oh Colby, we just adore him. He is a fantastic dog that truly deserves the best of homes. Colby loves people and likes to be close by them. A true Velcro dog. Colby is extremely respectful of human boundaries, he will not get on the couch or the bed, but will lay his head in your lap as you watch the evening news. Colby loves other dogs, but does need supervision when he plays, he is on the older side so if he plays to hard, he hurts the following day. Colby is fantastic with kids. He loves my 7month old so much. He will just lay next to her and watch her play with her toys, occasionally licking her head as he walks by. 

Colby does suffer from skin issues. He will likely require medication to treat his itchiness. The medication is approximately $80 a month. Without his skin medication he is itchy and uncomfortable, he will need someone committed to making sure he does not have a flare up and if he does treating it accordingly. Colby is also an older, large dogs. I suspect some arthritis. He really struggles walking on hard wood or other slippery surfaces. Carpet is preferred for him so he can get around comfortably, or at least some runners so he doesn't slide. GOOD NEWS! Colby has had a ProHeart 12 injection, this means he does not need Heart worm prevention for a full year (he had it 1/12/21)!
